                                                                                                                 ('Section 2: Chapter 2: Private International Law', 'Foundation Manual', 'What is the maximum number of ordinary judges in the High Court?', 'qa', '{"answer":"No more than 48 ordinary judges","justification":"No more than 48 ordinary judges"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Foundation'], 'Supreme Court Court of Appeal High Court Circuit Court District Court ESTABLISHED Section 1 Section 2 (as amended by Courts Section 2 Section 4 Section 5 BY Act 2019) ▪ * * * * Consists of ▪ The Chief Justice * President of the Court of Appeal * President of the High Court * President of the Circuit * President of the District Court Court ▪ 9 ordinary judges * No more than 18 ordinary judges* No more than 48 ordinary judges * No more than 71 ordinary * (Civil Law (Misc Prov) Act 2021 * No more than 45 ordinary judges ▪ President of Court of Appeal * Chief Justice & President of High judges * officio Court officio * Chief Justice officio * President of the District ▪ President of the High Court * President of Court of Appeal may Court officio * President of Court of Appeal officio request ordinary judge of High officio Court to sit * Up to 8 Specialist Judges▪ In case insufficient number of Personal Insolvency * President of the Circuit Court judges available, any ordinary * Chief Justice at request of officio judge of High Court requested by President of may request to sit in order to deal with a ordinary judge of Supreme Court particular matter to sit * Matter heard by* Divisions of 3 or 5 judges * Division of 3 for appeal cases * Usually one judge alone * One'),
                                                                                                                 ('Section 2: Chapter 2: Private International Law', 'Foundation Manual', 'Which courts are located exclusively in Dublin?', 'qa', '{"answer":"Supreme Court, Court of Appeal, High Court","justification":"* Dublin only * Dublin only * Dublin only except for two-week * 8 Circuits: Cork, Dublin, * 24 District Court regions location circuits twice yearly to each of the Eastern, Midland, * (The court has sat outside Dublin 8 circuits for: Northern, South East, on a select number of occasions South West and Western in more recent times)"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Foundation'], 'judge alone in civil * One judge alone matters * Must be at least 5 if * Procedural/interlocutory: * Jury required for: constitutionality of a law being President or one ordinary judge questioned sitting alone Defamation false imprisonment malicious prosecution * May sit in division of 7 to consider particularly important * 3 judges if President High Court constitutional cases has directed (cases of particular importance - rare) Supreme Court Court of Appeal High Court Circuit Court District Court * * * * * Geographical * Dublin only * Dublin only * Dublin only except for two-week * 8 Circuits: Cork, Dublin, * 24 District Court regions location circuits twice yearly to each of the Eastern, Midland, * (The court has sat outside Dublin 8 circuits for: Northern, South East, on a select number of occasions South West and Western in more recent times) - Appeals from Circuit Court * At least the following no. of - instance Personal Injuries judges assigned to each: cases Dublin - 10 The High Court also sits outside Dublin at different stages in anyo Cork - 3 legal term.'),
                                                                                                                 ('Section 2: Chapter 2: Private International Law', 'Foundation Manual', 'How many District Court regions are there?', 'qa', '{"answer":"24","justification":"* 24 District Court regions"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Foundation'], 'judge alone in civil * One judge alone matters * Must be at least 5 if * Procedural/interlocutory: * Jury required for: constitutionality of a law being President or one ordinary judge questioned sitting alone Defamation false imprisonment malicious prosecution * May sit in division of 7 to consider particularly important * 3 judges if President High Court constitutional cases has directed (cases of particular importance - rare) Supreme Court Court of Appeal High Court Circuit Court District Court * * * * * Geographical * Dublin only * Dublin only * Dublin only except for two-week * 8 Circuits: Cork, Dublin, * 24 District Court regions location circuits twice yearly to each of the Eastern, Midland, * (The court has sat outside Dublin 8 circuits for: Northern, South East, on a select number of occasions South West and Western in more recent times) - Appeals from Circuit Court * At least the following no. of - instance Personal Injuries judges assigned to each: cases Dublin - 10 The High Court also sits outside Dublin at different stages in anyo Cork - 3 legal term.'),
                                                                                                                 ('Section 2: Chapter 2: Private International Law', 'Foundation Manual', 'What category does ''Others - 1'' fall under in the civil court structure?', 'qa', '{"answer":"Others","justification":"Others"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Foundation'], 'Others - 1'),
                                                                                                                 ('Section 2: Chapter 2: Private International Law', 'Foundation Manual', 'What does private international law provide answers to?', 'qa', '{"answer":"Questions about where to sue, what law to apply, and how to enforce judgments in cases involving multiple countries.","justification":"Private international law, also referred to as conflicts of law, provides answers to these questions. It resolves the conflict between laws of different countries."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Foundation'], 'A straightforward court case involves an Irish judge, sitting in Ireland, applying Irish law to Irish parties. However, things are not always so simple. Suppose an Argentine on holiday in Ireland is run down by a Spaniard driving a German-built car, the brakes of which were faulty. Where should the victim sue? What law should the court apply? If the victim sues in Ireland and is successful, how can he or she enforce her judgment against the Spanish driver and the German car manufacturers? Private international law, also referred to as conflicts of law, provides answers to these questions. It resolves the conflict between laws of different countries. This is a hugely complex subject. Yet with increasing internationalisation, it is a subject which is of ever increasing relevance for legal practitioners. The purpose of this chapter is to give a brief overview of the most important principles of the subject and to outline the legislation which, to a certain extent, is replacing the old common law. PRIVATE INTERNATIONAL LAW IS A NATIONAL LAW SUBJECT Contrary to what its name might suggest, private international law is a matter of national law. That is, each state has confronted the sort of situations outlined in the first paragraph above and has attempted to evolve rules which are both practicable and fair. It follows that each state has its own private international law. The differences between different legal systems can be quite marked.'),
                                                                                                                 ('Section 2: Chapter 2: Private International Law', 'Foundation Manual', 'Is private international law a matter of national law?', 'qa', '{"answer":"Yes, each state has its own private international law.","justification":"Contrary to what its name might suggest, private international law is a matter of national law. That is, each state has confronted the sort of situations outlined in the first paragraph above and has attempted to evolve rules which are both practicable and fair. It follows that each state has its own private international law."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Foundation'], 'A straightforward court case involves an Irish judge, sitting in Ireland, applying Irish law to Irish parties. However, things are not always so simple. Suppose an Argentine on holiday in Ireland is run down by a Spaniard driving a German-built car, the brakes of which were faulty. Where should the victim sue? What law should the court apply? If the victim sues in Ireland and is successful, how can he or she enforce her judgment against the Spanish driver and the German car manufacturers? Private international law, also referred to as conflicts of law, provides answers to these questions. It resolves the conflict between laws of different countries. This is a hugely complex subject. Yet with increasing internationalisation, it is a subject which is of ever increasing relevance for legal practitioners. The purpose of this chapter is to give a brief overview of the most important principles of the subject and to outline the legislation which, to a certain extent, is replacing the old common law. PRIVATE INTERNATIONAL LAW IS A NATIONAL LAW SUBJECT Contrary to what its name might suggest, private international law is a matter of national law. That is, each state has confronted the sort of situations outlined in the first paragraph above and has attempted to evolve rules which are both practicable and fair. It follows that each state has its own private international law. The differences between different legal systems can be quite marked.'),
                                                                                                                 ('Section 2: Chapter 2: Private International Law', 'Foundation Manual', 'What are the three main objectives of private international law?', 'qa', '{"answer":"To establish jurisdiction, to determine the applicable law, and to enforce foreign judgments.","justification":"Private international law can be seen as fulfilling three objectives: * To establish the conditions under which a court is competent to hear a claim (jurisdiction); * To establish for each type of case the particular system of national law which should apply to that case (choice of law); * To establish the circumstances in which a foreign judgment is deemed decisive of a question in dispute and the circumstances in which the right vested in a judgment creditor by a foreign judgment can be enforced by an action in Ireland (enforcement of judgment)."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Foundation'], 'Within the context of the European Union, however, these differences are gradually becoming less pronounced. This is because several conventions, to which all members of the and EEA are signatories, have stipulated common rules for resolving the conflict of laws. These conventions are enacted by legislation in the legal systems of the contracting states and support the important objective of minimising the conflict between different conflict of laws rules. More recently, the European Union has adopted a number of Regulations, largely re-enacting the principles previously contained in the several conventions. OBJECTIVES OF PRIVATE INTERNATIONAL LAW Private international law can be seen as fulfilling three objectives: * To establish the conditions under which a court is competent to hear a claim (jurisdiction); * To establish for each type of case the particular system of national law which should apply to that case (choice of law); * To establish the circumstances in which a foreign judgment is deemed decisive of a question in dispute and the circumstances in which the right vested in a judgment creditor by a foreign judgment can be enforced by an action in Ireland (enforcement of judgment). It is important to remember that these are three discrete issues. Thus, it is quite possible that an Irish court could consider itself to have jurisdiction to hear a case yet consider itself obliged to apply the law of a different country to that case. Choice of law does not necessarily follow from choice of jurisdiction.'),
                                                                                                                 ('Section 2: Chapter 2: Private International Law', 'Foundation Manual', 'Can an Irish court have jurisdiction over a case but apply the law of another country?', 'qa', '{"answer":"Yes, an Irish court can have jurisdiction over a case but apply the law of another country.","justification":"It is important to remember that these are three discrete issues. Thus, it is quite possible that an Irish court could consider itself to have jurisdiction to hear a case yet consider itself obliged to apply the law of a different country to that case. Choice of law does not necessarily follow from choice of jurisdiction."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Foundation'], 'Within the context of the European Union, however, these differences are gradually becoming less pronounced. This is because several conventions, to which all members of the and EEA are signatories, have stipulated common rules for resolving the conflict of laws. These conventions are enacted by legislation in the legal systems of the contracting states and support the important objective of minimising the conflict between different conflict of laws rules. More recently, the European Union has adopted a number of Regulations, largely re-enacting the principles previously contained in the several conventions. OBJECTIVES OF PRIVATE INTERNATIONAL LAW Private international law can be seen as fulfilling three objectives: * To establish the conditions under which a court is competent to hear a claim (jurisdiction); * To establish for each type of case the particular system of national law which should apply to that case (choice of law); * To establish the circumstances in which a foreign judgment is deemed decisive of a question in dispute and the circumstances in which the right vested in a judgment creditor by a foreign judgment can be enforced by an action in Ireland (enforcement of judgment). It is important to remember that these are three discrete issues. Thus, it is quite possible that an Irish court could consider itself to have jurisdiction to hear a case yet consider itself obliged to apply the law of a different country to that case. Choice of law does not necessarily follow from choice of jurisdiction.'),
                                                                                                                 ('Section 2: Chapter 2: Private International Law', 'Foundation Manual', 'What legislation gave effect to the Brussels Convention and the Lugano Convention in Irish law?', 'qa', '{"answer":"The Jurisdiction of Courts and Enforcement of Judgments (European Communities) Act 1998","justification":"the Jurisdiction of Courts and Enforcement of Judgments (European Communities) Act 1998, which gave effect to certain international Conventions in Irish law e.g. the Brussels Convention and the Lugano Convention"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Foundation'], 'BASIC RULES Traditional common law rules of private international law used to establish whether a court had jurisdiction to hear a particular case. These laws were largely superseded by certain legislation, the most recent being the Jurisdiction of Courts and Enforcement of Judgments (European Communities) Act 1998, which gave effect to certain international Conventions in Irish law e.g. the Brussels Convention and the Lugano Convention. These Conventions identified the circumstances in which a person domiciled in a contracting state could be sued before the courts of another contracting state. The Brussels Convention on jurisdiction and the enforcement of judgments in civil and commercial matters 1968 concerns civil and commercial matters as between contracting states. The Jurisdiction of Courts and Enforcement of Judgments (Amendment) Act 2012 - gives effect in Irish law to the 2007 Lugano Convention. Non-EU EFTA (European Free Trade Area) Member States (Norway, Iceland, Switzerland), as well as Member States, contract to this latter convention. The provisions of the Lugano Convention are almost, but not entirely, the same as the provisions of the Brussels Convention. Thus, you should take extra care when dealing with a case involving Norway, Switzerland or Iceland. matters were governed by Council Regulation 44/2001 (Brussels Regulation) of 22 December 2000 on jurisdiction and the recognition and enforcement of judgments in civil and commercial matters. It was adopted to ensure that these matters were covered throughout the European Union by a directly applicable European Union law instrument.'),
                                                                                                                 ('Section 2: Chapter 2: Private International Law', 'Foundation Manual', 'Which countries are parties to the Lugano Convention?', 'qa', '{"answer":"Member States, Norway, Iceland, and Switzerland","justification":"Non-EU EFTA (European Free Trade Area) Member States (Norway, Iceland, Switzerland), as well as Member States, contract to this latter convention"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Foundation'], 'BASIC RULES Traditional common law rules of private international law used to establish whether a court had jurisdiction to hear a particular case. These laws were largely superseded by certain legislation, the most recent being the Jurisdiction of Courts and Enforcement of Judgments (European Communities) Act 1998, which gave effect to certain international Conventions in Irish law e.g. the Brussels Convention and the Lugano Convention. These Conventions identified the circumstances in which a person domiciled in a contracting state could be sued before the courts of another contracting state. The Brussels Convention on jurisdiction and the enforcement of judgments in civil and commercial matters 1968 concerns civil and commercial matters as between contracting states. The Jurisdiction of Courts and Enforcement of Judgments (Amendment) Act 2012 - gives effect in Irish law to the 2007 Lugano Convention. Non-EU EFTA (European Free Trade Area) Member States (Norway, Iceland, Switzerland), as well as Member States, contract to this latter convention. The provisions of the Lugano Convention are almost, but not entirely, the same as the provisions of the Brussels Convention. Thus, you should take extra care when dealing with a case involving Norway, Switzerland or Iceland. matters were governed by Council Regulation 44/2001 (Brussels Regulation) of 22 December 2000 on jurisdiction and the recognition and enforcement of judgments in civil and commercial matters. It was adopted to ensure that these matters were covered throughout the European Union by a directly applicable European Union law instrument.'),
                                                                                                                 ('Section 2: Chapter 2: Private International Law', 'Foundation Manual', 'When did Regulation 1215/2012 come into force?', 'qa', '{"answer":"January 2015","justification":"Since January 2015 Regulation 1215/2012 is in force."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Foundation'], 'Since January 2015 Regulation 1215/2012 is in force. It is a recast of the provisions contained in Brussels and repeals Brussels altogether. The Recast Regulation applies to legal proceedings instituted (and to judgments rendered) on or after January 2015. Article 68 of Regulation 1215/2012 provides that as between the Member States, it supersedes the 1968 Brussels Convention, except as regards the territories of the Member States which fall within the territorial scope of the 1968 Convention and which are excluded from Regulation 1215/2012 pursuant to Article 355 of the TFEU. While most territories/countries are included - exclusions include French Overseas Territories/Collectives. Some of the details of Regulation 1215/2012 are set out below. MATTERS COVERED BY THE BRUSSELS CONVENTION Article 1 of Regulation 1215/2012 states that the Convention applies to all civil and commercial matters, apart from: * Revenue, customs or administrative matters; * The status or capacity of natural persons; * Rights in property arising out of a matrimonial relationship, apart from maintenance payments; * Wills and succession; * Bankruptcy; * Proceedings relating to the winding up of insolvent companies or other legal persons; * Judicial arrangements, compositions and analogous proceedings; * Social security; * Arbitration. Regulation 1215/2012 provides that in so far as it replaces the provisions of the 1968 Brussels Convention between the Member States, any reference to that Convention shall be understood as a reference to Regulation 1215/2012.'),
                                                                                                                 ('Section 2: Chapter 2: Private International Law', 'Foundation Manual', 'What does Regulation 1215/2012 apply to?', 'qa', '{"answer":"All civil and commercial matters except revenue, customs or administrative matters, status or capacity of natural persons, rights in property arising out of a matrimonial relationship (except maintenance payments), wills and succession, bankruptcy, proceedings relating to the winding up of insolvent companies or other legal persons, judicial arrangements, compositions and analogous proceedings, social security, and arbitration.","justification":"Article 1 of Regulation 1215/2012 states that the Convention applies to all civil and commercial matters, apart from: * Revenue, customs or administrative matters; * The status or capacity of natural persons; * Rights in property arising out of a matrimonial relationship, apart from maintenance payments; * Wills and succession; * Bankruptcy; * Proceedings relating to the winding up of insolvent companies or other legal persons; * Judicial arrangements, compositions and analogous proceedings; * Social security; * Arbitration."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Foundation'], 'Since January 2015 Regulation 1215/2012 is in force. It is a recast of the provisions contained in Brussels and repeals Brussels altogether. The Recast Regulation applies to legal proceedings instituted (and to judgments rendered) on or after January 2015. Article 68 of Regulation 1215/2012 provides that as between the Member States, it supersedes the 1968 Brussels Convention, except as regards the territories of the Member States which fall within the territorial scope of the 1968 Convention and which are excluded from Regulation 1215/2012 pursuant to Article 355 of the TFEU. While most territories/countries are included - exclusions include French Overseas Territories/Collectives. Some of the details of Regulation 1215/2012 are set out below. MATTERS COVERED BY THE BRUSSELS CONVENTION Article 1 of Regulation 1215/2012 states that the Convention applies to all civil and commercial matters, apart from: * Revenue, customs or administrative matters; * The status or capacity of natural persons; * Rights in property arising out of a matrimonial relationship, apart from maintenance payments; * Wills and succession; * Bankruptcy; * Proceedings relating to the winding up of insolvent companies or other legal persons; * Judicial arrangements, compositions and analogous proceedings; * Social security; * Arbitration. Regulation 1215/2012 provides that in so far as it replaces the provisions of the 1968 Brussels Convention between the Member States, any reference to that Convention shall be understood as a reference to Regulation 1215/2012.'),
                                                                                                                 ('Section 2: Chapter 2: Private International Law', 'Foundation Manual', 'Under Regulation 1215/2012, where are persons domiciled in a Member State normally sued?', 'qa', '{"answer":"In the courts of that Member State","justification":"persons domiciled in a Member State shall, whatever their nationality, be sued in the courts of that Member State"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Foundation'], 'PERSONS DOMICILED IN A CONTRACTING STATE WILL NORMALLY BE SUED IN THAT STATE Article 4 of Regulation 1215/2012 provides: Subject to the provisions of this Regulation, persons domiciled in a Member State shall, whatever their nationality, be sued in the courts of that Member State. There are exceptions to this. 1. Article 24 contains a number of exclusive jurisdiction rules which might vest competence in the courts of another Member State. 2. Article 25 provides recognition for valid jurisdiction agreements entered into by the parties which confer jurisdiction on the courts of another Member State. 3. Article 27 provides that, where proceedings between the same parties and involving the same cause of action have been commenced in another Member State, all courts other than that first seised must decline jurisdiction. 4. Articles 10-23 establish special rules for insurance, consumer and employment contracts. If these exceptions do not apply, the crucial question is that of domicile. Article 62 of Regulation 1215/2012 provides that, where courts of a Member State are seised of a matter, they apply their own internal law to determine whether a party is domiciled in that Member State. If a party is not domiciled there and the courts wish to determine whether a party is domiciled in another particular Contracting State, the courts should apply the law of that contracting state.'),
                                                                                                                 ('Section 2: Chapter 2: Private International Law', 'Foundation Manual', 'According to Regulation 1215/2012, what law do courts apply to determine if a party is domiciled in a Member State?', 'qa', '{"answer":"Their own internal law","justification":"they apply their own internal law to determine whether a party is domiciled in that Member State"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Foundation'], 'PERSONS DOMICILED IN A CONTRACTING STATE WILL NORMALLY BE SUED IN THAT STATE Article 4 of Regulation 1215/2012 provides: Subject to the provisions of this Regulation, persons domiciled in a Member State shall, whatever their nationality, be sued in the courts of that Member State. There are exceptions to this. 1. Article 24 contains a number of exclusive jurisdiction rules which might vest competence in the courts of another Member State. 2. Article 25 provides recognition for valid jurisdiction agreements entered into by the parties which confer jurisdiction on the courts of another Member State. 3. Article 27 provides that, where proceedings between the same parties and involving the same cause of action have been commenced in another Member State, all courts other than that first seised must decline jurisdiction. 4. Articles 10-23 establish special rules for insurance, consumer and employment contracts. If these exceptions do not apply, the crucial question is that of domicile. Article 62 of Regulation 1215/2012 provides that, where courts of a Member State are seised of a matter, they apply their own internal law to determine whether a party is domiciled in that Member State. If a party is not domiciled there and the courts wish to determine whether a party is domiciled in another particular Contracting State, the courts should apply the law of that contracting state.'),
                                                                                                                 ('Section 2: Chapter 2: Private International Law', 'Foundation Manual', 'What does the term ''domicile'' mean under the Fifth Schedule to the 1988 Act and section of the 2012 Amendment Act?', 'qa', '{"answer":"Domicile is defined as being ''ordinarily resident in the State''.","justification":"the Fifth Schedule to the 1988 Act and section of the 2012 Amendment Act adopt a definition of \"domicile\" which effectively turns on whether the party is \"ordinarily resident in the State\""}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Foundation'], 'Note, the Fifth Schedule to the 1988 Act and section of the 2012 Amendment Act adopt a definition of "domicile" which effectively turns on whether the party is "ordinarily resident in the State". This is distinct from the traditional common law definition of domicile. Ordinary residence is not statutorily defined but has been judicially considered in the context of tax law. It seems to require that the residence is not casual and uncertain but has some degree of continuity. Article 63 of Regulation 1215/2012 provides that the domicile of a company (or other legal person or association of natural or legal persons) is where it has its statutory seat, central administration or principal place of business. Article 63(2) of 1215/2012 specifies that, for Ireland and the "statutory seat" means registered office if there is one. EXCEPTIONS TO THE "DOMICILED" RULE Article 7 of Regulation 1215/2012 establishes a number of special jurisdictions whereby persons domiciled in one Contracting State may be sued in another Contracting State. These jurisdictions have been judicially considered by the European Court of Justice, the authoritative interpreter of the Convention. For the exact contours of each exception, therefore, one should refer to the jurisprudence of that court.'),
                                                                                                                 ('Section 2: Chapter 2: Private International Law', 'Foundation Manual', 'According to Regulation 1215/2012, where is the domicile of a company located?', 'qa', '{"answer":"The domicile of a company is where it has its statutory seat, central administration or principal place of business.","justification":"Article 63 of Regulation 1215/2012 provides that the domicile of a company (or other legal person or association of natural or legal persons) is where it has its statutory seat, central administration or principal place of business."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Foundation'], 'Note, the Fifth Schedule to the 1988 Act and section of the 2012 Amendment Act adopt a definition of "domicile" which effectively turns on whether the party is "ordinarily resident in the State". This is distinct from the traditional common law definition of domicile. Ordinary residence is not statutorily defined but has been judicially considered in the context of tax law. It seems to require that the residence is not casual and uncertain but has some degree of continuity. Article 63 of Regulation 1215/2012 provides that the domicile of a company (or other legal person or association of natural or legal persons) is where it has its statutory seat, central administration or principal place of business. Article 63(2) of 1215/2012 specifies that, for Ireland and the "statutory seat" means registered office if there is one. EXCEPTIONS TO THE "DOMICILED" RULE Article 7 of Regulation 1215/2012 establishes a number of special jurisdictions whereby persons domiciled in one Contracting State may be sued in another Contracting State. These jurisdictions have been judicially considered by the European Court of Justice, the authoritative interpreter of the Convention. For the exact contours of each exception, therefore, one should refer to the jurisprudence of that court.'),
                                                                                                                 ('Section 2: Chapter 2: Private International Law', 'Foundation Manual', 'In matters relating to contract, where should the case be heard?', 'qa', '{"answer":"In the courts for the place of performance of the obligation in question.","justification":"In matters relating to contract, in the courts for the place of performance of the obligation in question;"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Foundation'], 'It is worth noting, however, some of the main categories: * In matters relating to contract, in the courts for the place of performance of the obligation in question; * In matters relating to tort, in the courts for the place where the harmful event occurred; * As regards a dispute arising out of the operations of a branch, agency or other establishment, in the courts for the place in which the branch, agency or other establishment is situated. Article 8 of 1215/2012 aims at avoiding a multiplicity of actions by allowing co-defendants to be sued and third party issues to be tried in the same court that is seised of the initial proceedings. Articles 17 and 18 of 1215/2012 must be considered when the plaintiff asserts that a contract was entered and that the Plaintiff is a ''consumer''. In Harkin Towpik & Ors. [2013] IEHC 351 Kearns in the High Court considered an application brought by the Defendants to set aside the service on them of a personal injury summons arising out of a medical procedure which the Plaintiff underwent in Poland having first engaged the Defendants on their website. The Court acceded to the Defendants'' application on the grounds that the court had no jurisdiction to hear and determine the plaintiff''s claim, as claimed under the Brussels Regulation (44/2001).'),
                                                                                                                 ('Section 2: Chapter 2: Private International Law', 'Foundation Manual', 'What does Article 8 of 1215/2012 aim to prevent?', 'qa', '{"answer":"A multiplicity of actions by allowing co-defendants to be sued and third party issues to be tried in the same court.","justification":"Article 8 of 1215/2012 aims at avoiding a multiplicity of actions by allowing co-defendants to be sued and third party issues to be tried in the same court that is seised of the initial proceedings."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Foundation'], 'It is worth noting, however, some of the main categories: * In matters relating to contract, in the courts for the place of performance of the obligation in question; * In matters relating to tort, in the courts for the place where the harmful event occurred; * As regards a dispute arising out of the operations of a branch, agency or other establishment, in the courts for the place in which the branch, agency or other establishment is situated. Article 8 of 1215/2012 aims at avoiding a multiplicity of actions by allowing co-defendants to be sued and third party issues to be tried in the same court that is seised of the initial proceedings. Articles 17 and 18 of 1215/2012 must be considered when the plaintiff asserts that a contract was entered and that the Plaintiff is a ''consumer''. In Harkin Towpik & Ors. [2013] IEHC 351 Kearns in the High Court considered an application brought by the Defendants to set aside the service on them of a personal injury summons arising out of a medical procedure which the Plaintiff underwent in Poland having first engaged the Defendants on their website. The Court acceded to the Defendants'' application on the grounds that the court had no jurisdiction to hear and determine the plaintiff''s claim, as claimed under the Brussels Regulation (44/2001).'),
                                                                                                                 ('Section 2: Chapter 2: Private International Law', 'Foundation Manual', 'What does Article 16 of the Brussels Regulation allow a consumer to choose as jurisdictions?', 'qa', '{"answer":"Either where the other party is domiciled or where the consumer is domiciled","justification":"Article 16 gives a consumer a choice of jurisdiction within which to bring proceedings: either where the other party is domiciled or where the consumer is domiciled."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Foundation'], 'The Plaintiff had sought to invoke Articles 15 and 16 of the regulation which affords "protective" jurisdiction in respect of certain parties identified as the weaker party in the case of a contract, including consumers. Article 16 gives a consumer a choice of jurisdiction within which to bring proceedings: either where the other party is domiciled or where the consumer is domiciled. The plaintiff claimed she was entitled to sue in Ireland because (a) she was a consumer and she entered a contract for services with persons providing professional services who had "directed" their activities to this State. Article 15(1) of 44/2001 (now Article 17(1) of 1215/2012) provides that a consumer contract is one which is entered into by a person outside of his or her trade or profession, and where, among other things, the: "contract has been concluded with a person who pursues commercial or professional activities in the Member State of the consumer''s domicile or directs such activities to that Member State or to several States including that Member State, and the contract falls within the scope of such activities." Kearns setting aside the service of the summons upon the defendants on the grounds that the Court did not have jurisdiction to hear and determine the plaintiff''s claim against those Defendants held that; There is no evidence before the court to indicate that the defendants directed their activities in any specific way to the Irish market.'),
                                                                                                                 ('Section 2: Chapter 2: Private International Law', 'Foundation Manual', 'According to Kearns what was the reason for setting aside the service of the summons?', 'qa', '{"answer":"There is no evidence that the defendants directed their activities in any specific way to the Irish market","justification":"There is no evidence before the court to indicate that the defendants directed their activities in any specific way to the Irish market."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Foundation'], 'The Plaintiff had sought to invoke Articles 15 and 16 of the regulation which affords "protective" jurisdiction in respect of certain parties identified as the weaker party in the case of a contract, including consumers. Article 16 gives a consumer a choice of jurisdiction within which to bring proceedings: either where the other party is domiciled or where the consumer is domiciled. The plaintiff claimed she was entitled to sue in Ireland because (a) she was a consumer and she entered a contract for services with persons providing professional services who had "directed" their activities to this State. Article 15(1) of 44/2001 (now Article 17(1) of 1215/2012) provides that a consumer contract is one which is entered into by a person outside of his or her trade or profession, and where, among other things, the: "contract has been concluded with a person who pursues commercial or professional activities in the Member State of the consumer''s domicile or directs such activities to that Member State or to several States including that Member State, and the contract falls within the scope of such activities." Kearns setting aside the service of the summons upon the defendants on the grounds that the Court did not have jurisdiction to hear and determine the plaintiff''s claim against those Defendants held that; There is no evidence before the court to indicate that the defendants directed their activities in any specific way to the Irish market.'),
                                                                                                                 ('Section 2: Chapter 2: Private International Law', 'Foundation Manual', 'What does the presence of a domain name and an English telephone number on the defendants'' website indicate?', 'qa', '{"answer":"Indicates that the defendants'' activities are likely directed towards consumers outside of Ireland.","justification":"The defendants'' website has a United Kingdom domain name, and the contact telephone number provided to the plaintiff by the third named defendant is an English telephone number. It is not preceded with an international dialling code."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Foundation'], 'The defendants'' website has a United Kingdom domain name, and the contact telephone number provided to the plaintiff by the third named defendant is an English telephone number. It is not preceded with an international dialling code. The currency dealt with was not Euro, but Sterling. Furthermore, the plaintiff only met the first named defendant for the first time in Poland and was only examined for the first time in Poland, where she also underwent pre-operative tests for the first time. Significantly, it was in Poland that the breast reduction procedure was performed. Although she may have transferred monies constituting a deposit from her bank account in Ireland, this was only a nominal sum in relation to the total cost of the procedure, and the remaining cost of the surgery was paid in Poland. In addition, the plaintiff had signed a consent form while in Poland. All of these matters suggest that the defendants'' activities were not directed to consumers within this jurisdiction.'),
                                                                                                                 ('Section 2: Chapter 2: Private International Law', 'Foundation Manual', 'Where did the plaintiff undergo the breast reduction procedure?', 'qa', '{"answer":"Poland.","justification":"Significantly, it was in Poland that the breast reduction procedure was performed."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Foundation'], 'The defendants'' website has a United Kingdom domain name, and the contact telephone number provided to the plaintiff by the third named defendant is an English telephone number. It is not preceded with an international dialling code. The currency dealt with was not Euro, but Sterling. Furthermore, the plaintiff only met the first named defendant for the first time in Poland and was only examined for the first time in Poland, where she also underwent pre-operative tests for the first time. Significantly, it was in Poland that the breast reduction procedure was performed. Although she may have transferred monies constituting a deposit from her bank account in Ireland, this was only a nominal sum in relation to the total cost of the procedure, and the remaining cost of the surgery was paid in Poland. In addition, the plaintiff had signed a consent form while in Poland. All of these matters suggest that the defendants'' activities were not directed to consumers within this jurisdiction.'),
                                                                                                                 ('Section 2: Chapter 2: Private International Law', 'Foundation Manual', 'What courts have exclusive jurisdiction over proceedings concerning the validity of the constitution, nullity or dissolution of companies?', 'qa', '{"answer":"The courts of the Contracting State where the company has its seat.","justification":"the courts of the Contracting State in which the company, legal person or association has its seat"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Foundation'], 'Article 24 of 1215/2012 grants exclusive jurisdiction in respect of certain matters to the following courts: * in proceedings which have as their object rights in rem in, or tenancies of, immovable property, the courts of the Contracting State in which the property is situated; * in proceedings which have as their object the validity of the constitution, the nullity or the dissolution of companies or other legal persons or associations of natural or legal persons, or the decisions of their organs, the courts of the Contracting State in which the company, legal person or association has its seat; * in proceedings which have as their object the validity of entries in public registers, the courts of the Contracting State in which the register is kept; * in proceedings concerned with the registration or validity of patents, trademarks, designs, or other similar rights required to be deposited or registered, the courts of the Contracting State in which the deposit or registration has been applied for, has taken place or is under the terms of an international convention deemed to have taken place; * in proceedings concerned with the enforcement of judgments, the courts of the Contracting State in which the judgment has been or is to be enforced.'),
                                                                                                                 ('Section 2: Chapter 2: Private International Law', 'Foundation Manual', 'What courts have exclusive jurisdiction over proceedings concerning the enforcement of judgments?', 'qa', '{"answer":"The courts of the Contracting State where the judgment has been or is to be enforced.","justification":"the courts of the Contracting State in which the judgment has been or is to be enforced"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Foundation'], 'Article 24 of 1215/2012 grants exclusive jurisdiction in respect of certain matters to the following courts: * in proceedings which have as their object rights in rem in, or tenancies of, immovable property, the courts of the Contracting State in which the property is situated; * in proceedings which have as their object the validity of the constitution, the nullity or the dissolution of companies or other legal persons or associations of natural or legal persons, or the decisions of their organs, the courts of the Contracting State in which the company, legal person or association has its seat; * in proceedings which have as their object the validity of entries in public registers, the courts of the Contracting State in which the register is kept; * in proceedings concerned with the registration or validity of patents, trademarks, designs, or other similar rights required to be deposited or registered, the courts of the Contracting State in which the deposit or registration has been applied for, has taken place or is under the terms of an international convention deemed to have taken place; * in proceedings concerned with the enforcement of judgments, the courts of the Contracting State in which the judgment has been or is to be enforced.'),
                                                                                                                 ('Section 2: Chapter 2: Private International Law', 'Foundation Manual', 'What does Order 11 of the Rules of the Superior Courts require for serving originating documents outside the jurisdiction?', 'qa', '{"answer":"The leave of the Court must be first obtained.","justification":"Order 11 of the Rules of the Superior Courts, 1986 as amended allows for service outside the jurisdiction of originating documents only if the leave of the Court is first obtained."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Foundation'], 'These will be more fully considered in the Civil Practice Course. For present purposes, it suffices to note the following: Order 11 of the Rules of the Superior Courts, 1986 as amended allows for service outside the jurisdiction of originating documents only if the leave of the Court is first obtained. Note Order 11 was recently amended by 362 of 2024. Giving effect to Regulation 1215/2012 (previously 44/2001), Order 11A of the Rules provides that in the case of proceedings to which Article 1 of Regulation 1215/2012 or Article 1 of the Lugano Convention apply, an originating summons can be served outside the jurisdiction without the leave of the Court if it complies with specified formalities. Order applies to proceedings which are governed by the terms of the 1968 Brussels Convention and Part of the Jurisdiction of Courts and Enforcement of Judgments Act 1998 (1968 Convention) - i.e. countries or territories included in the scope of the 1968 Convention that are outside the scope of Regulation 1215/2012. Order provides further rules relating to the service of originating documents outside the jurisdiction where the subject-matter and proposed defendant are covered by Council Regulation 2201/2003 (family law matters - see Regulation for details). Orders and apply to the manner of physical service of documents.'),
                                                                                                                 ('Section 2: Chapter 2: Private International Law', 'Foundation Manual', 'Under what circumstances can an originating summons be served outside the jurisdiction without the leave of the Court according to Order 11A?', 'qa', '{"answer":"When proceedings are covered by Article 1 of Regulation 1215/2012 or Article 1 of the Lugano Convention and comply with specified formalities.","justification":"Order 11A of the Rules provides that in the case of proceedings to which Article 1 of Regulation 1215/2012 or Article 1 of the Lugano Convention apply, an originating summons can be served outside the jurisdiction without the leave of the Court if it complies with specified formalities."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Foundation'], 'These will be more fully considered in the Civil Practice Course. For present purposes, it suffices to note the following: Order 11 of the Rules of the Superior Courts, 1986 as amended allows for service outside the jurisdiction of originating documents only if the leave of the Court is first obtained. Note Order 11 was recently amended by 362 of 2024. Giving effect to Regulation 1215/2012 (previously 44/2001), Order 11A of the Rules provides that in the case of proceedings to which Article 1 of Regulation 1215/2012 or Article 1 of the Lugano Convention apply, an originating summons can be served outside the jurisdiction without the leave of the Court if it complies with specified formalities. Order applies to proceedings which are governed by the terms of the 1968 Brussels Convention and Part of the Jurisdiction of Courts and Enforcement of Judgments Act 1998 (1968 Convention) - i.e. countries or territories included in the scope of the 1968 Convention that are outside the scope of Regulation 1215/2012. Order provides further rules relating to the service of originating documents outside the jurisdiction where the subject-matter and proposed defendant are covered by Council Regulation 2201/2003 (family law matters - see Regulation for details). Orders and apply to the manner of physical service of documents.'),
                                                                                                                 ('Section 2: Chapter 2: Private International Law', 'Foundation Manual', 'What are the traditional rules on jurisdiction for defendants within the jurisdiction?', 'qa', '{"answer":"The Irish courts have jurisdiction where an originating summons has been validly served.","justification":"These rules are procedural in focus, stipulating that the Irish courts have jurisdiction where an originating summons has been validly served."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Foundation'], 'TRADITIONAL RULES OF JURISDICTION (FOR COUNTRIES NOT GOVERNED BY THE ABOVE REGULATIONS & CONVENTIONS) DEFENDANT WITHIN THE JURISDICTION The traditional rules on jurisdiction obviously still apply outside the context of the abovementioned Regulations and Conventions. These rules are procedural in focus, stipulating that the Irish courts have jurisdiction where an originating summons has been validly served. This causes few difficulties where the intended defendant is in the State, capable of being served. A person outside the jurisdiction can voluntarily submit to Irish jurisdiction by instructing a solicitor to accept service, by entering an unconditional appearance to the action, by commencing an action as a plaintiff, by seeking interlocutory relief that is consistent only with an intention to contest the case on its merits and by agreement, through contract, to submit to the jurisdiction. DEFENDANT OUTSIDE THE JURISDICTION (ORDER 11 RSC) However, one may have an intended defendant outside the jurisdiction who does not voluntarily submit herself to the jurisdiction. Each court sets out the requirements for example, Order 11 of the Rules of the Superior Courts deals with this problem, outside the geographic and subject-matter context of the Brussels Convention, by permitting the High Court to allow service outside the jurisdiction. (For the Circuit Court - See Order 13 CCR for details, for the District Court - see Order 41A DCR for details). Order 11 Rule 1 (a) to identifies the (22) circumstances in which the Court may make an order allowing service outside the jurisdiction.'),
                                                                                                                 ('Section 2: Chapter 2: Private International Law', 'Foundation Manual', 'How can a defendant outside the jurisdiction voluntarily submit to Irish jurisdiction?', 'qa', '{"answer":"By instructing a solicitor to accept service, by entering an unconditional appearance to the action, by commencing an action as a plaintiff, by seeking interlocutory relief that is consistent only with an intention to contest the case on its merits and by agreement, through contract, to submit to the jurisdiction.","justification":"A person outside the jurisdiction can voluntarily submit to Irish jurisdiction by instructing a solicitor to accept service, by entering an unconditional appearance to the action, by commencing an action as a plaintiff, by seeking interlocutory relief that is consistent only with an intention to contest the case on its merits and by agreement, through contract, to submit to the jurisdiction."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Foundation'], 'TRADITIONAL RULES OF JURISDICTION (FOR COUNTRIES NOT GOVERNED BY THE ABOVE REGULATIONS & CONVENTIONS) DEFENDANT WITHIN THE JURISDICTION The traditional rules on jurisdiction obviously still apply outside the context of the abovementioned Regulations and Conventions. These rules are procedural in focus, stipulating that the Irish courts have jurisdiction where an originating summons has been validly served. This causes few difficulties where the intended defendant is in the State, capable of being served. A person outside the jurisdiction can voluntarily submit to Irish jurisdiction by instructing a solicitor to accept service, by entering an unconditional appearance to the action, by commencing an action as a plaintiff, by seeking interlocutory relief that is consistent only with an intention to contest the case on its merits and by agreement, through contract, to submit to the jurisdiction. DEFENDANT OUTSIDE THE JURISDICTION (ORDER 11 RSC) However, one may have an intended defendant outside the jurisdiction who does not voluntarily submit herself to the jurisdiction. Each court sets out the requirements for example, Order 11 of the Rules of the Superior Courts deals with this problem, outside the geographic and subject-matter context of the Brussels Convention, by permitting the High Court to allow service outside the jurisdiction. (For the Circuit Court - See Order 13 CCR for details, for the District Court - see Order 41A DCR for details). Order 11 Rule 1 (a) to identifies the (22) circumstances in which the Court may make an order allowing service outside the jurisdiction.'),
                                                                                                                 ('Section 2: Chapter 2: Private International Law', 'Foundation Manual', 'What must the plaintiff demonstrate to obtain leave for service outside the jurisdiction?', 'qa', '{"answer":"The plaintiff must show that Ireland is the forum conveniens for the action.","justification":"In effect, the intending plaintiff must show that Ireland is the forum conveniens for the action (see Order 11, Rule 2)."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Foundation'], 'For instance, such an order may be granted where the whole subject matter of the action is land situate within the jurisdiction (with or without rents or profits). Order 11 Rule 5 provides that the plaintiff''s application must be supported by evidence (affidavit evidence is permissible) stating that in the belief of the deponent the plaintiff has a good cause of action; showing in what place or country such defendant is or probably may be found and whether such defendant is a citizen of Ireland; identifying the particular sub-head of sub-rule (1) under which leave is sought and setting out and verifying the facts which it is alleged establish the particular provision(s) The Court can only grant leave if the Court is satisfied that the case is a proper one for service outside the jurisdiction. In effect, the intending plaintiff must show that Ireland is the forum conveniens for the action (see Order 11, Rule 2). Thus, even if the action falls within one of the categories of Order 11 Rule 1, the Court will not allow service out of the jurisdiction if to do so would put a defendant to unwarranted expense and inconvenience.'),
                                                                                                                 ('Section 2: Chapter 2: Private International Law', 'Foundation Manual', 'Under what circumstances will the court deny leave for service out of the jurisdiction?', 'qa', '{"answer":"If allowing service out of the jurisdiction would put the defendant to unwarranted expense and inconvenience.","justification":"Thus, even if the action falls within one of the categories of Order 11 Rule 1, the Court will not allow service out of the jurisdiction if to do so would put a defendant to unwarranted expense and inconvenience."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Foundation'], 'For instance, such an order may be granted where the whole subject matter of the action is land situate within the jurisdiction (with or without rents or profits). Order 11 Rule 5 provides that the plaintiff''s application must be supported by evidence (affidavit evidence is permissible) stating that in the belief of the deponent the plaintiff has a good cause of action; showing in what place or country such defendant is or probably may be found and whether such defendant is a citizen of Ireland; identifying the particular sub-head of sub-rule (1) under which leave is sought and setting out and verifying the facts which it is alleged establish the particular provision(s) The Court can only grant leave if the Court is satisfied that the case is a proper one for service outside the jurisdiction. In effect, the intending plaintiff must show that Ireland is the forum conveniens for the action (see Order 11, Rule 2). Thus, even if the action falls within one of the categories of Order 11 Rule 1, the Court will not allow service out of the jurisdiction if to do so would put a defendant to unwarranted expense and inconvenience.'),
                                                                                                                 ('Section 2: Chapter 2: Private International Law', 'Foundation Manual', 'What determines the law to be applied in a case before an Irish court?', 'qa', '{"answer":"The determination of jurisdiction does not determine the applicable law; instead, it involves distinguishing between procedural and substantive law issues.","justification":"the determination of jurisdiction does not determine what law should be applied to the resolution of the action"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Foundation'], 'As noted at the outset, the determination of jurisdiction does not determine what law should be applied to the resolution of the action. For instance, an action before an Irish court might involve a tort committed abroad. The first point to note here is the difference between substantive and procedural law issues. All procedural issues are resolved by reference to the law of the forum; the substantive rights of the parties may be guaranteed by a foreign law. Although some laws are clearly procedural and some are clearly substantive, others are more difficult to classify. Consider the requirement in the Statute of Frauds that certain contracts be evidenced in writing in order to be enforceable. In Leroux Brown (1852) 12 801 the English courts held this to be a procedural rule, thereby depriving the French plaintiff of the benefits of a French contract which would have been enforceable under the law governing the contract. This decision has been criticised. For present purposes it suffices to note that the division between substance and procedure is not always straightforward. Different rules apply to different substantive areas of law. In developing appropriate rules, courts - and legislators - attempt to ascertain to which jurisdiction the alleged legal wrong is most closely connected. In some instances, all the connecting factors may face one way. In other instances, however, different connecting factors compete for attention. These will be considered briefly below.'),
                                                                                                                 ('Section 2: Chapter 2: Private International Law', 'Foundation Manual', 'How are procedural and substantive law issues treated differently in a case before an Irish court?', 'qa', '{"answer":"Procedural issues are resolved by the law of the forum, while substantive rights may be governed by foreign law.","justification":"All procedural issues are resolved by reference to the law of the forum; the substantive rights of the parties may be guaranteed by a foreign law"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Foundation'], 'As noted at the outset, the determination of jurisdiction does not determine what law should be applied to the resolution of the action. For instance, an action before an Irish court might involve a tort committed abroad. The first point to note here is the difference between substantive and procedural law issues. All procedural issues are resolved by reference to the law of the forum; the substantive rights of the parties may be guaranteed by a foreign law. Although some laws are clearly procedural and some are clearly substantive, others are more difficult to classify. Consider the requirement in the Statute of Frauds that certain contracts be evidenced in writing in order to be enforceable. In Leroux Brown (1852) 12 801 the English courts held this to be a procedural rule, thereby depriving the French plaintiff of the benefits of a French contract which would have been enforceable under the law governing the contract. This decision has been criticised. For present purposes it suffices to note that the division between substance and procedure is not always straightforward. Different rules apply to different substantive areas of law. In developing appropriate rules, courts - and legislators - attempt to ascertain to which jurisdiction the alleged legal wrong is most closely connected. In some instances, all the connecting factors may face one way. In other instances, however, different connecting factors compete for attention. These will be considered briefly below.'),
                                                                                                                 ('Section 2: Chapter 2: Private International Law', 'Foundation Manual', 'What does the lex fori theory suggest about the choice of law in tort cases?', 'qa', '{"answer":"The law of the forum should apply, similar to criminal law.","justification":"This analogises torts law to criminal law and argues that the law of the forum should apply. In effect, this allows the jurisdictional issue, considered above, to determine the choice of law."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Foundation'], 'As with the laws governing jurisdiction, considered above, the traditional laws governing choice of law are being gradually superseded by international conventions, particularly within the context of the Family law matters, in particular, have been the subject of conventions. For present purposes, however, it suffices to examine the main rules governing torts and contract. TORTS Cheshire and North note some of the difficulties raised by an attempt to establish the appropriate law for a torts case. Different connecting factors may compete: the place where the tort was committed; the residence, ordinary residence, domicile or nationality of the parties; the place where the parties'' relationship was centred. Further, where the wrongful act takes place in one country and the consequential harm in another country, there is a definitional problem in saying where the tort was committed. Should the same law cover all issues, including capacity, vicarious liability, and rules on remoteness? Should the same rule apply to the different types of tort? Finally, other countries recognise torts (civil wrongs) which are not recognised in Irish law and which may reflect different philosophical standpoints. There is a dearth of case law concerning this area of the law and a number of competing theories have been identified below: * The lex fori : This analogises torts law to criminal law and argues that the law of the forum should apply. In effect, this allows the jurisdictional issue, considered above, to determine the choice of law.'),
                                                                                                                 ('Section 2: Chapter 2: Private International Law', 'Foundation Manual', 'What are some connecting factors that may compete when determining the appropriate law for a torts case?', 'qa', '{"answer":"The place where the tort was committed, the residence, ordinary residence, domicile or nationality of the parties, and the place where the parties'' relationship was centred.","justification":"Different connecting factors may compete: the place where the tort was committed; the residence, ordinary residence, domicile or nationality of the parties; the place where the parties'' relationship was centred."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Foundation'], 'As with the laws governing jurisdiction, considered above, the traditional laws governing choice of law are being gradually superseded by international conventions, particularly within the context of the Family law matters, in particular, have been the subject of conventions. For present purposes, however, it suffices to examine the main rules governing torts and contract. TORTS Cheshire and North note some of the difficulties raised by an attempt to establish the appropriate law for a torts case. Different connecting factors may compete: the place where the tort was committed; the residence, ordinary residence, domicile or nationality of the parties; the place where the parties'' relationship was centred. Further, where the wrongful act takes place in one country and the consequential harm in another country, there is a definitional problem in saying where the tort was committed. Should the same law cover all issues, including capacity, vicarious liability, and rules on remoteness? Should the same rule apply to the different types of tort? Finally, other countries recognise torts (civil wrongs) which are not recognised in Irish law and which may reflect different philosophical standpoints. There is a dearth of case law concerning this area of the law and a number of competing theories have been identified below: * The lex fori : This analogises torts law to criminal law and argues that the law of the forum should apply. In effect, this allows the jurisdictional issue, considered above, to determine the choice of law.'),
                                                                                                                 ('Section 2: Chapter 2: Private International Law', 'Foundation Manual', 'What does ''lex loci delicti'' refer to?', 'qa', '{"answer":"The law of the place where the tort was committed","justification":"This suggests that the law of the place where the tort was committed should apply."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Foundation'], '* The lex loci delicti :, (particularly in European civil law jurisdictions). This suggests that the law of the place where the tort was committed should apply. This raises the difficulty, adverted to above, of ascertaining where the tort was committed. For instance, the tort of negligence requires the existence of a duty of care, breach of that duty, damage and a causal connection between the breach and the damage. Thus is the tort committed where the duty of care comes into existence, the breach committed or the damage suffered, assuming these to be different? * The "proper law of tort". This advocates a flexible approach which allows the court to consider all the different connecting factors. In Grehan Medical Incorporated and Valley Pines Associates [1986] ILRM 627, the Supreme Court appeared to favour a more flexible approach to the choice of law in torts than had previously been adopted. This suggested something akin to the proper law of tort, but its scope is unclear. Further, the comments of Walsh in this regard were obiter, a point noted by Keane in An Bord Tráchtála Waterford Foods Plc (unreported, High Court, 25 November 1992). In that case, Keane was content to apply the lex loci delicti, noting that reform in this area might be a matter more for the legislature than the courts.'),
                                                                                                                 ('Section 2: Chapter 2: Private International Law', 'Foundation Manual', 'What did the Supreme Court appear to favor in Grehan Medical Incorporated and Valley Pines Associates?', 'qa', '{"answer":"A more flexible approach to the choice of law in torts","justification":"the Supreme Court appeared to favour a more flexible approach to the choice of law in torts than had previously been adopted."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Foundation'], '* The lex loci delicti :, (particularly in European civil law jurisdictions). This suggests that the law of the place where the tort was committed should apply. This raises the difficulty, adverted to above, of ascertaining where the tort was committed. For instance, the tort of negligence requires the existence of a duty of care, breach of that duty, damage and a causal connection between the breach and the damage. Thus is the tort committed where the duty of care comes into existence, the breach committed or the damage suffered, assuming these to be different? * The "proper law of tort". This advocates a flexible approach which allows the court to consider all the different connecting factors. In Grehan Medical Incorporated and Valley Pines Associates [1986] ILRM 627, the Supreme Court appeared to favour a more flexible approach to the choice of law in torts than had previously been adopted. This suggested something akin to the proper law of tort, but its scope is unclear. Further, the comments of Walsh in this regard were obiter, a point noted by Keane in An Bord Tráchtála Waterford Foods Plc (unreported, High Court, 25 November 1992). In that case, Keane was content to apply the lex loci delicti, noting that reform in this area might be a matter more for the legislature than the courts.'),
                                                                                                                 ('Section 2: Chapter 2: Private International Law', 'Foundation Manual', 'What is the name of the regulation that clarifies the area in relation to European Union Member States?', 'qa', '{"answer":"Regulation 864/2007 (Rome","justification":"Regulation 864/2007 (Rome"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Foundation'], 'There has been clarification of the area in relation to European Union Member States in the form of Regulation 864/2007 (Rome - applicable from the January 2009 concerning acts that occurred after the August 2007.'),
                                                                                                                 ('Section 2: Chapter 2: Private International Law', 'Foundation Manual', 'From what date is Regulation 864/2007 (Rome applicable?', 'qa', '{"answer":"January 2009","justification":"applicable from the January 2009"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Foundation'], 'There has been clarification of the area in relation to European Union Member States in the form of Regulation 864/2007 (Rome - applicable from the January 2009 concerning acts that occurred after the August 2007.'),
                                                                                                                 ('Section 2: Chapter 2: Private International Law', 'Foundation Manual', 'What is Regulation 864/2007 commonly known as?', 'qa', '{"answer":"Rome","justification":"(ROME"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Foundation'], 'REGULATION 864/2007 (ROME THE LAW APPLICABLE TO NON-'),
                                                                                                                 ('Section 2: Chapter 2: Private International Law', 'Foundation Manual', 'What is the primary law applicable in cases involving non-contractual obligations under Regulation No. 864/2007?', 'qa', '{"answer":"The law of the country where the damage occurs","justification":"the law of the country where the damage occurs"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Foundation'], 'Prior to this Regulation Member States had no common rules to designate the applicable law in non-contractual matters, legal solutions have varied widely from one Member State to another, and it was tempting for parties to refer disputes to the court which applied the most favourable law to them (known as "forum shopping"). Regulation No. 864/2007 defines the rules applicable to non-contractual obligations in civil and commercial matters, including product liability, acts relating to the affairs of another person and non-contractual obligations arising out of dealings before the conclusion of a contract. The Regulation applies from 11 January 2009 in all Member States except Denmark and applies to events giving rise to damage that occurred after the August 2007 (date of entry into force). It does not attempt to harmonise the substantive law of the signatories in the field of non-contractual obligations, but only their conflict-of-law rules, so that, no matter where in the an action is brought, the rules determining the applicable law will always be the same. As a general rule, and in order of priority, the law applicable is (see Article 4 (and also Clause 18 of Preamble) of the Regulation: * the law of the country where the damage occurs; * the law of the country where both parties were habitually resident when the damage occurred; * the law of the country with which the case is manifestly more closely connected than the other countries.'),
                                                                                                                 ('Section 2: Chapter 2: Private International Law', 'Foundation Manual', 'What is the second applicable law if the first option cannot be determined?', 'qa', '{"answer":"The law of the country where both parties were habitually resident when the damage occurred","justification":"the law of the country where both parties were habitually resident when the damage occurred"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Foundation'], 'Prior to this Regulation Member States had no common rules to designate the applicable law in non-contractual matters, legal solutions have varied widely from one Member State to another, and it was tempting for parties to refer disputes to the court which applied the most favourable law to them (known as "forum shopping"). Regulation No. 864/2007 defines the rules applicable to non-contractual obligations in civil and commercial matters, including product liability, acts relating to the affairs of another person and non-contractual obligations arising out of dealings before the conclusion of a contract. The Regulation applies from 11 January 2009 in all Member States except Denmark and applies to events giving rise to damage that occurred after the August 2007 (date of entry into force). It does not attempt to harmonise the substantive law of the signatories in the field of non-contractual obligations, but only their conflict-of-law rules, so that, no matter where in the an action is brought, the rules determining the applicable law will always be the same. As a general rule, and in order of priority, the law applicable is (see Article 4 (and also Clause 18 of Preamble) of the Regulation: * the law of the country where the damage occurs; * the law of the country where both parties were habitually resident when the damage occurred; * the law of the country with which the case is manifestly more closely connected than the other countries.'),
                                                                                                                 ('Section 2: Chapter 2: Private International Law', 'Foundation Manual', 'What types of matters are excluded from the choice of applicable law?', 'qa', '{"answer":"Revenue, customs and administrative matters, the liability of the State, and matrimonial and family relationships.","justification":"certain matters are excluded, e.g. revenue, customs and administrative matters, the liability of the State, and matrimonial and family relationships"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Foundation'], 'The parties can choose, by mutual agreement, the law that will be applicable to their obligation. Specific rules are provided for certain matters, e.g. product liability and intellectual property, and certain matters are excluded, e.g. revenue, customs and administrative matters, the liability of the State, and matrimonial and family relationships. DEFINING THE APPLICABLE LAW The law applicable to non-contractual obligations under this Regulation governs: * the basis and extent of liability, including the persons who may be held liable; * the grounds for exemption from liability; the limitation or division of liability; * the existence, nature and assessment of damage and the remedy claimed; * the measures that the court may take to prevent or end injury or damage and provide for compensation (within the limits of national procedural law); * the transferability of the right to seek compensation, including by succession; * the persons entitled to compensation for damage sustained personally; * liability for the acts of another person; * extinction of obligations, and the rules relating to prescription or limitation based on a period of time. Article 4 provides the general rule: the law applicable to a non-contractual obligation arising out of a tort is the law of the country in which the damage occurs, regardless of the country or countries in which indirect consequences of the event may occur.'),
                                                                                                                 ('Section 2: Chapter 2: Private International Law', 'Foundation Manual', 'According to Article 4, what is the general rule for the law applicable to a non-contractual obligation arising out of a tort?', 'qa', '{"answer":"The law applicable to a non-contractual obligation arising out of a tort is the law of the country in which the damage occurs, regardless of the country or countries in which indirect consequences of the event may occur.","justification":"the law applicable to a non-contractual obligation arising out of a tort is the law of the country in which the damage occurs, regardless of the country or countries in which indirect consequences of the event may occur"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Foundation'], 'The parties can choose, by mutual agreement, the law that will be applicable to their obligation. Specific rules are provided for certain matters, e.g. product liability and intellectual property, and certain matters are excluded, e.g. revenue, customs and administrative matters, the liability of the State, and matrimonial and family relationships. DEFINING THE APPLICABLE LAW The law applicable to non-contractual obligations under this Regulation governs: * the basis and extent of liability, including the persons who may be held liable; * the grounds for exemption from liability; the limitation or division of liability; * the existence, nature and assessment of damage and the remedy claimed; * the measures that the court may take to prevent or end injury or damage and provide for compensation (within the limits of national procedural law); * the transferability of the right to seek compensation, including by succession; * the persons entitled to compensation for damage sustained personally; * liability for the acts of another person; * extinction of obligations, and the rules relating to prescription or limitation based on a period of time. Article 4 provides the general rule: the law applicable to a non-contractual obligation arising out of a tort is the law of the country in which the damage occurs, regardless of the country or countries in which indirect consequences of the event may occur.'),
                                                                                                                 ('Section 2: Chapter 2: Private International Law', 'Foundation Manual', 'What happens if the defendant and claimant are both habitually resident in the same country at the time of damage?', 'qa', '{"answer":"The law of that country applies.","justification":"When the defendant and the claimant are both habitually resident in the same country at the time when the damage occurs, it is the law of that country that applies."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Foundation'], 'There are, however, two major exceptions: (1) When the defendant and the claimant are both habitually resident in the same country at the time when the damage occurs, it is the law of that country that applies. (2) When the event is manifestly more closely connected with a different country (e.g. deriving from a pre-existing relationship between the parties, such as a contract), it is the law of that country that applies. Article 14 provides that the parties are free to choose the law applicable to a noncontractual obligation either by common agreement after the event giving rise to the damage or, between business people, by an agreement freely negotiated before the event giving rise to the damage. The choice must be explicit or evident from the circumstances and must not prejudice the rights of any third party. This freedom of choice cannot be invoked when all the elements relevant to the situation relate to a country other than the one chosen. (Note: The freedom of choice cannot be invoked in relation to Infringement of Intellectual Property Rights and also in relation to Unfair Competition and Acts Restricting Free Competition). law overrides the law of a non-EU country, chosen by the parties, when all the elements of the situation are located in one or more Member States. Article 10 deals with unjust enrichment, including undue payments. The applicable law is that governing a pre-existing relationship between the parties, e.g.'),
                                                                                                                 ('Section 2: Chapter 2: Private International Law', 'Foundation Manual', 'Under what conditions can parties choose the law applicable to a noncontractual obligation?', 'qa', '{"answer":"Parties can choose the law applicable to a noncontractual obligation either by common agreement after the event giving rise to the damage or, between business people, by an agreement freely negotiated before the event giving rise to the damage.","justification":"Article 14 provides that the parties are free to choose the law applicable to a noncontractual obligation either by common agreement after the event giving rise to the damage or, between business people, by an agreement freely negotiated before the event giving rise to the damage."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Foundation'], 'There are, however, two major exceptions: (1) When the defendant and the claimant are both habitually resident in the same country at the time when the damage occurs, it is the law of that country that applies. (2) When the event is manifestly more closely connected with a different country (e.g. deriving from a pre-existing relationship between the parties, such as a contract), it is the law of that country that applies. Article 14 provides that the parties are free to choose the law applicable to a noncontractual obligation either by common agreement after the event giving rise to the damage or, between business people, by an agreement freely negotiated before the event giving rise to the damage. The choice must be explicit or evident from the circumstances and must not prejudice the rights of any third party. This freedom of choice cannot be invoked when all the elements relevant to the situation relate to a country other than the one chosen. (Note: The freedom of choice cannot be invoked in relation to Infringement of Intellectual Property Rights and also in relation to Unfair Competition and Acts Restricting Free Competition). law overrides the law of a non-EU country, chosen by the parties, when all the elements of the situation are located in one or more Member States. Article 10 deals with unjust enrichment, including undue payments. The applicable law is that governing a pre-existing relationship between the parties, e.g.'),
                                                                                                                 ('Section 2: Chapter 2: Private International Law', 'Foundation Manual', 'What is the applicable law if both parties were habitually resident in the same country where the event giving rise to the unjust enrichment occurred?', 'qa', '{"answer":"The law of that country applies.","justification":"If there is no such relationship, but both parties were habitually resident in the same country where the event giving rise to the unjust enrichment occurred, it is the law of that country that applies."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Foundation'], 'a contract or a harmful event closely connected with the unjust enrichment. If there is no such relationship, but both parties were habitually resident in the same country where the event giving rise to the unjust enrichment occurred, it is the law of that country that applies. Failing that, the applicable law is that of the country in which the unjust enrichment occurred or, if the event is manifestly more closely linked with another country, the law of that other country. This also applies to the law governing an existing relationship between the parties, or failing that the law of the country of habitual residence, or failing that the law of the country in which the acts were performed or, finally, the law of the country with which the matter is most closely connected). Article 12: culpa in contrahendo: non-contractual obligations arising out of dealings before the conclusion of a contract), the applicable law is that governing the contract (regardless of whether the contract was actually concluded or not). If the law cannot be determined, the applicable law is that of the country in which the damage occurred, or failing that the law of the country where both parties are habitually resident or of the country most closely associated with the event.'),
                                                                                                                 ('Section 2: Chapter 2: Private International Law', 'Foundation Manual', 'What is the applicable law if the law cannot be determined for non-contractual obligations arising out of dealings before the conclusion of a contract?', 'qa', '{"answer":"The applicable law is that of the country in which the damage occurred, or failing that the law of the country where both parties are habitually resident or of the country most closely associated with the event.","justification":"If the law cannot be determined, the applicable law is that of the country in which the damage occurred, or failing that the law of the country where both parties are habitually resident or of the country most closely associated with the event."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Foundation'], 'a contract or a harmful event closely connected with the unjust enrichment. If there is no such relationship, but both parties were habitually resident in the same country where the event giving rise to the unjust enrichment occurred, it is the law of that country that applies. Failing that, the applicable law is that of the country in which the unjust enrichment occurred or, if the event is manifestly more closely linked with another country, the law of that other country. This also applies to the law governing an existing relationship between the parties, or failing that the law of the country of habitual residence, or failing that the law of the country in which the acts were performed or, finally, the law of the country with which the matter is most closely connected). Article 12: culpa in contrahendo: non-contractual obligations arising out of dealings before the conclusion of a contract), the applicable law is that governing the contract (regardless of whether the contract was actually concluded or not). If the law cannot be determined, the applicable law is that of the country in which the damage occurred, or failing that the law of the country where both parties are habitually resident or of the country most closely associated with the event.'),
                                                                                                                 ('Section 2: Chapter 2: Private International Law', 'Foundation Manual', 'What is the applicable law for product liability under Article 5?', 'qa', '{"answer":"The law of the habitual residence of the person sustaining the damage at the time the damage occurred, if the product is marketed in that country; otherwise, the law of the country in which the product was purchased; otherwise, the law of the country in which the damage occurred, if the product is marketed there.","justification":"The law of the habitual residence of the person sustaining the damage at the time the damage occurred, if the product is marketed in that country; otherwise, the law of the country in which the product was purchased; otherwise, the law of the country in which the damage occurred, if the product is marketed there."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Foundation'], 'The Regulation (864/2007) makes specific provision in relation to the following areas: * Product liability (Article 5) The law of the habitual residence of the person sustaining the damage at the time the damage occurred, if the product is marketed in that country; otherwise, the law of the country in which the product was purchased; otherwise, the law of the country in which the damage occurred, if the product is marketed there. But if the defendant could not foresee the marketing of the product in one of the other countries as above, the law applicable is that of his habitual residence. If the harmful event is closely connected with a different country, then it is the law of that country that is applicable. * Unfair competition and acts restricting free competition (Article 6) For non-contractual obligations resulting from an act of unfair competition, the applicable law is that of the country in which competition or the collective interests of consumers are or are likely to be affected, unless the act affects only the interests of a specific competitor, in which case the general rule laid down in Article 4 applies. For non-contractual obligations resulting from an act restricting free competition, the applicable law is that of the country in which the market is or is likely to be affected.'),
                                                                                                                 ('Section 2: Chapter 2: Private International Law', 'Foundation Manual', 'What is the applicable law for non-contractual obligations resulting from an act of unfair competition under Article 6?', 'qa', '{"answer":"The applicable law is that of the country in which competition or the collective interests of consumers are or are likely to be affected, unless the act affects only the interests of a specific competitor, in which case the general rule laid down in Article 4 applies.","justification":"For non-contractual obligations resulting from an act of unfair competition, the applicable law is that of the country in which competition or the collective interests of consumers are or are likely to be affected, unless the act affects only the interests of a specific competitor, in which case the general rule laid down in Article 4 applies."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Foundation'], 'The Regulation (864/2007) makes specific provision in relation to the following areas: * Product liability (Article 5) The law of the habitual residence of the person sustaining the damage at the time the damage occurred, if the product is marketed in that country; otherwise, the law of the country in which the product was purchased; otherwise, the law of the country in which the damage occurred, if the product is marketed there. But if the defendant could not foresee the marketing of the product in one of the other countries as above, the law applicable is that of his habitual residence. If the harmful event is closely connected with a different country, then it is the law of that country that is applicable. * Unfair competition and acts restricting free competition (Article 6) For non-contractual obligations resulting from an act of unfair competition, the applicable law is that of the country in which competition or the collective interests of consumers are or are likely to be affected, unless the act affects only the interests of a specific competitor, in which case the general rule laid down in Article 4 applies. For non-contractual obligations resulting from an act restricting free competition, the applicable law is that of the country in which the market is or is likely to be affected.'),
                                                                                                                 ('Section 2: Chapter 2: Private International Law', 'Foundation Manual', 'What is the law applicable to a non-contractual obligation resulting from the infringement of an intellectual property right?', 'qa', '{"answer":"The law applicable is that of the country for which the protection was sought.","justification":"The law applicable to a non-contractual obligation resulting from the infringement of an intellectual property right is that of the country for which the protection was sought."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Foundation'], 'When this applies to more than one country, a claimant suing in the domicile of the defendant can choose the law of that country, provided that the market in that country is affected. A claimant suing more than one defendant in the court of the defendant''s domicile can choose the law of that court only if the act restricting competition affects the market in that Member State. * Environmental damage (Article 7) The general rule applies, unless the claimant chooses to base his action on the law of the Member State in which the harmful event occurred. * Infringement of intellectual property rights (Article 8) The law applicable to a non-contractual obligation resulting from the infringement of an intellectual property right is that of the country for which the protection was sought. There can be no derogation to this provision. The law applicable in these cases cannot be derogated from by an agreement under Article 14 of this Regulation, which allows the parties to choose the law applicable to a non-contractual obligation by common consent. * Industrial action (Article 9) The law applicable to a non-contractual obligation relating to the liability of a worker, employer or professional association resulting from damage caused by a strike or lockout, whether in progress or after the event, is that of the country in which the industrial action is taken.'),
                                                                                                                 ('Section 2: Chapter 2: Private International Law', 'Foundation Manual', 'Can the law applicable to a non-contractual obligation resulting from the infringement of an intellectual property right be derogated from?', 'qa', '{"answer":"No, there can be no derogation to this provision.","justification":"There can be no derogation to this provision."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Foundation'], 'When this applies to more than one country, a claimant suing in the domicile of the defendant can choose the law of that country, provided that the market in that country is affected. A claimant suing more than one defendant in the court of the defendant''s domicile can choose the law of that court only if the act restricting competition affects the market in that Member State. * Environmental damage (Article 7) The general rule applies, unless the claimant chooses to base his action on the law of the Member State in which the harmful event occurred. * Infringement of intellectual property rights (Article 8) The law applicable to a non-contractual obligation resulting from the infringement of an intellectual property right is that of the country for which the protection was sought. There can be no derogation to this provision. The law applicable in these cases cannot be derogated from by an agreement under Article 14 of this Regulation, which allows the parties to choose the law applicable to a non-contractual obligation by common consent. * Industrial action (Article 9) The law applicable to a non-contractual obligation relating to the liability of a worker, employer or professional association resulting from damage caused by a strike or lockout, whether in progress or after the event, is that of the country in which the industrial action is taken.'),
                                                                                                                 ('Section 2: Chapter 2: Private International Law', 'Foundation Manual', 'What types of obligations are excluded from the Regulation?', 'qa', '{"answer":"Revenue, customs or administrative matters, state liability, and non-contractual obligations arising out of family or similar relations, matrimonial property regimes, wills and successions, bills of exchange, cheques, promissory notes, company law, trust relations, nuclear damage, and violations of privacy and rights relating to personality.","justification":"The Regulation does not apply to revenue, customs or administrative matters, to the liability of the State, or to non-contractual obligations arising out of: * family or similar relations, including obligations of maintenance; * matrimonial property regimes and similar, wills and successions; * bills of exchange, cheques, promissory notes and other negotiable instruments; * the law of companies, in relation to e.g. their creation and legal capacity, liability of members, etc.; * relations between the settlers, trustees and beneficiaries of a trust created voluntarily; * nuclear damage; * violations of privacy and rights relating to personality, including defamation."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Foundation'], 'Matters excluded The Regulation does not apply to revenue, customs or administrative matters, to the liability of the State, or to non-contractual obligations arising out of: * family or similar relations, including obligations of maintenance; * matrimonial property regimes and similar, wills and successions; * bills of exchange, cheques, promissory notes and other negotiable instruments; * the law of companies, in relation to e.g. their creation and legal capacity, liability of members, etc.; * relations between the settlers, trustees and beneficiaries of a trust created voluntarily; * nuclear damage; * violations of privacy and rights relating to personality, including defamation. RELATIONSHIP WITH EXISTING INTERNATIONAL CONVENTIONS The Regulation does not affect the application of international conventions governing noncontractual obligations to which one or more Member States are parties. Between Member States, the Regulation overrides conventions concluded exclusively between them to the extent that these concern the matters it covers. CONTRACT THE ROME CONVENTION Ireland is a signatory to the 1980 Rome Convention on the Law Applicable to Contractual Obligations. The purpose of this Convention is to establish uniform choice of law rules for contractual obligations throughout the Ireland has implemented this Convention in terms of the Contractual Obligations (Applicable Law) Act 1991. This Act simply provides that the Convention will have the force of law in the State. Article 1 provides that the rules of the Convention apply to contractual obligations in any situation involving a choice between the laws of different countries.'),
                                                                                                                 ('Section 2: Chapter 2: Private International Law', 'Foundation Manual', 'Which convention does Ireland implement through the Contractual Obligations (Applicable Law) Act 1991?', 'qa', '{"answer":"The 1980 Rome Convention on the Law Applicable to Contractual Obligations.","justification":"Ireland is a signatory to the 1980 Rome Convention on the Law Applicable to Contractual Obligations. The purpose of this Convention is to establish uniform choice of law rules for contractual obligations throughout the Ireland has implemented this Convention in terms of the Contractual Obligations (Applicable Law) Act 1991. This Act simply provides that the Convention will have the force of law in the State."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Foundation'], 'Matters excluded The Regulation does not apply to revenue, customs or administrative matters, to the liability of the State, or to non-contractual obligations arising out of: * family or similar relations, including obligations of maintenance; * matrimonial property regimes and similar, wills and successions; * bills of exchange, cheques, promissory notes and other negotiable instruments; * the law of companies, in relation to e.g. their creation and legal capacity, liability of members, etc.; * relations between the settlers, trustees and beneficiaries of a trust created voluntarily; * nuclear damage; * violations of privacy and rights relating to personality, including defamation. RELATIONSHIP WITH EXISTING INTERNATIONAL CONVENTIONS The Regulation does not affect the application of international conventions governing noncontractual obligations to which one or more Member States are parties. Between Member States, the Regulation overrides conventions concluded exclusively between them to the extent that these concern the matters it covers. CONTRACT THE ROME CONVENTION Ireland is a signatory to the 1980 Rome Convention on the Law Applicable to Contractual Obligations. The purpose of this Convention is to establish uniform choice of law rules for contractual obligations throughout the Ireland has implemented this Convention in terms of the Contractual Obligations (Applicable Law) Act 1991. This Act simply provides that the Convention will have the force of law in the State. Article 1 provides that the rules of the Convention apply to contractual obligations in any situation involving a choice between the laws of different countries.'),
                                                                                                                 ('Section 2: Chapter 2: Private International Law', 'Foundation Manual', 'Which types of contracts are excluded from the scope of the Rome Regulation?', 'qa', '{"answer":"Contracts arising out of family relationships","justification":"Certain types of contract are excluded from the scope of the Regulation and these are set out in Article 1, paragraph 2 for example obligations arising out of family relationships."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Foundation'], 'However, certain types of contracts, such as contractual obligations arising out of a family relationship, are not subject to the rules. Article 3 establishes that the parties are free to choose which law will govern their contract. Article 4 provides that, in the absence of a choice, the law which governs the contract will be the law of the country with which the contract is most closely related. Article 4 provides guidance, in the form of rebuttable presumptions, as to what this means. Article 5 provides special rules for certain consumer contracts while Article 6 provides special rules for individual employment contracts. The Convention has many other detailed provisions covering issues such as capacity, validity, subrogation and burden of proof. ROME REGULATION 593/2008 The Rome Regulation came into force on the December 2009 and applies to all contracts made after that date. It replaces the Rome Convention 1980 in the Member States and it changes the law in a number of ways. It will apply to all member states excluding Denmark. A copy of the Regulation is included in the Appendix to this manual. Note that while Recital 45 of the Regulation indicates that the United Kingdom is not taking part in the adoption of the Regulation, it subsequently chose to adopt it. Certain types of contract are excluded from the scope of the Regulation and these are set out in Article 1, paragraph 2 for example obligations arising out of family relationships.'),
                                                                                                                 ('Section 2: Chapter 2: Private International Law', 'Foundation Manual', 'What happens if the parties do not choose the governing law for their contract under the Rome Regulation?', 'qa', '{"answer":"The law of the country with which the contract is most closely related will govern the contract","justification":"Article 4 provides that, in the absence of a choice, the law which governs the contract will be the law of the country with which the contract is most closely related."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Foundation'], 'However, certain types of contracts, such as contractual obligations arising out of a family relationship, are not subject to the rules. Article 3 establishes that the parties are free to choose which law will govern their contract. Article 4 provides that, in the absence of a choice, the law which governs the contract will be the law of the country with which the contract is most closely related. Article 4 provides guidance, in the form of rebuttable presumptions, as to what this means. Article 5 provides special rules for certain consumer contracts while Article 6 provides special rules for individual employment contracts. The Convention has many other detailed provisions covering issues such as capacity, validity, subrogation and burden of proof. ROME REGULATION 593/2008 The Rome Regulation came into force on the December 2009 and applies to all contracts made after that date. It replaces the Rome Convention 1980 in the Member States and it changes the law in a number of ways. It will apply to all member states excluding Denmark. A copy of the Regulation is included in the Appendix to this manual. Note that while Recital 45 of the Regulation indicates that the United Kingdom is not taking part in the adoption of the Regulation, it subsequently chose to adopt it. Certain types of contract are excluded from the scope of the Regulation and these are set out in Article 1, paragraph 2 for example obligations arising out of family relationships.'),
                                                                                                                 ('Section 2: Chapter 2: Private International Law', 'Foundation Manual', 'What happens if the parties do not choose the applicable law for their contract?', 'qa', '{"answer":"If the parties do not choose the applicable law, Article 4 sets out how the law governing the contract will be determined.","justification":"If the parties have not chosen the law in accordance with Article 3, Article 4 sets out at paragraphs (a) to without prejudice to Articles 5 to 8 of the Regulation the manner in which the law governing the contract will be determined."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Foundation'], 'Article 3 provides for freedom of choice of the parties. The parties can select the law applicable to the whole or part only of the contract. If the parties have not chosen the law in accordance with Article 3, Article 4 sets out at paragraphs (a) to without prejudice to Articles 5 to 8 of the Regulation the manner in which the law governing the contract will be determined. For example, at 4(a) a contract for the sale of goods shall be governed by the law of the country where the seller has his habitual residence; a contract for the provision of services shall be governed by the law of the country where the service provider has his habitual residence. Articles 5 to 8 deal with specific types of contract: Article 5: Contracts of Carriage; Article 6: Consumer Contracts; Article 7: Insurance Contracts; Article 8: Individual employment contracts. Article 9 provides for certain overriding mandatory provisions which are stated as being provisions the respect for which is regarded as crucial by a country for safeguarding its public interests. Notwithstanding that the applicable law may have been chosen by the parties, a court can give effect to the overriding mandatory provisions of the law of the country where the obligations have to be or have been performed in so far as those overriding mandatory provisions render the performance of the contract unlawful.'),
                                                                                                                 ('Section 2: Chapter 2: Private International Law', 'Foundation Manual', 'What does Article 9 provide for in terms of overriding mandatory provisions?', 'qa', '{"answer":"Article 9 provides for certain overriding mandatory provisions that are crucial for safeguarding public interests.","justification":"Article 9 provides for certain overriding mandatory provisions which are stated as being provisions the respect for which is regarded as crucial by a country for safeguarding its public interests."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Foundation'], 'Article 3 provides for freedom of choice of the parties. The parties can select the law applicable to the whole or part only of the contract. If the parties have not chosen the law in accordance with Article 3, Article 4 sets out at paragraphs (a) to without prejudice to Articles 5 to 8 of the Regulation the manner in which the law governing the contract will be determined. For example, at 4(a) a contract for the sale of goods shall be governed by the law of the country where the seller has his habitual residence; a contract for the provision of services shall be governed by the law of the country where the service provider has his habitual residence. Articles 5 to 8 deal with specific types of contract: Article 5: Contracts of Carriage; Article 6: Consumer Contracts; Article 7: Insurance Contracts; Article 8: Individual employment contracts. Article 9 provides for certain overriding mandatory provisions which are stated as being provisions the respect for which is regarded as crucial by a country for safeguarding its public interests. Notwithstanding that the applicable law may have been chosen by the parties, a court can give effect to the overriding mandatory provisions of the law of the country where the obligations have to be or have been performed in so far as those overriding mandatory provisions render the performance of the contract unlawful.'),
                                                                                                                 ('Section 2: Chapter 2: Private International Law', 'Foundation Manual', 'What principle does the court generally follow when determining the proper law of a contract?', 'qa', '{"answer":"The court gives priority to the parties'' choice of law, whether it is expressly stated or clearly implicit.","justification":"First, the court should generally give priority to the parties'' choice of law, whether this is expressly stated or clearly implicit."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Foundation'], 'The Regulation affects a range of contracts and students should be familiar with the content and application of same. THE COMMON LAW The Common Law rules continue to apply outside the geographic and subject-matter context of the Convention. Traditionally, the common law favoured a test of lex loci contractus, applying to the contract the law of the place where the contract was formed. Over time, however, the courts have moved to an approach based on the "proper law of the contract". This approach is somewhat similar to that adopted by the Convention although, as a common law conception, is obviously more amenable to judicial interpretation and development. This less rigid approach attempts to identify the law which has the closest and most real connection with the contract and transaction. This operates on the basis of two principles. First, the court should generally give priority to the parties'' choice of law, whether this is expressly stated or clearly implicit. Secondly, if there is no such clear choice on the part of the parties, the court should identify the law which should govern the contract having regard to the circumstances of the case. As with all common law rules, these are not as straightforward as they might initially appear; you should refer yourself to the specialist textbooks if you need to advise on a particular situation.'),
                                                                                                                 ('Section 2: Chapter 2: Private International Law', 'Foundation Manual', 'If there is no clear choice of law by the parties, what does the court do?', 'qa', '{"answer":"The court identifies the law which should govern the contract having regard to the circumstances of the case.","justification":"Secondly, if there is no such clear choice on the part of the parties, the court should identify the law which should govern the contract having regard to the circumstances of the case."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Foundation'], 'The Regulation affects a range of contracts and students should be familiar with the content and application of same. THE COMMON LAW The Common Law rules continue to apply outside the geographic and subject-matter context of the Convention. Traditionally, the common law favoured a test of lex loci contractus, applying to the contract the law of the place where the contract was formed. Over time, however, the courts have moved to an approach based on the "proper law of the contract". This approach is somewhat similar to that adopted by the Convention although, as a common law conception, is obviously more amenable to judicial interpretation and development. This less rigid approach attempts to identify the law which has the closest and most real connection with the contract and transaction. This operates on the basis of two principles. First, the court should generally give priority to the parties'' choice of law, whether this is expressly stated or clearly implicit. Secondly, if there is no such clear choice on the part of the parties, the court should identify the law which should govern the contract having regard to the circumstances of the case. As with all common law rules, these are not as straightforward as they might initially appear; you should refer yourself to the specialist textbooks if you need to advise on a particular situation.'),
                                                                                                                 ('Section 2: Chapter 2: Private International Law', 'Foundation Manual', 'What regulation supersedes the Brussels Convention for recognition and enforcement of judgments?', 'qa', '{"answer":"Regulation 1215/2012","justification":"This has now been superseded by Regulation - see Regulation 1215/2012."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Foundation'], 'BASIC PRINCIPLES This is the final major area of private international law: in what circumstances will a court in this jurisdiction recognise and enforce a judgment given by a court in another jurisdiction. Originally the subject of common law rules, this area was then governed by the Brussels Convention, rendering the situation somewhat clearer, at least as regards the Member States contracting to that convention. This has now been superseded by Regulation - see Regulation 1215/2012. REGULATION 1215/2012 RECOGNITION DISTINGUISHED FROM ENFORCEMENT It should be noted that recognition is different to enforcement in that a court could recognise a judgment given in another state without enforcing it. For instance, a judgment of a foreign court might become relevant in the course of proceedings in an Irish court. In this context, Articles 36-38 of Regulation 1215/2012 (previously Articles 33-37 of Regulation 44/2001) deal with the recognition of foreign judgments. On the other hand, a person who has received judgment against a defendant in a foreign court, and who wishes to enforce that judgment against assets of the defendant present in Ireland, would seek both recognition and enforcement. THE RECOGNITION OF FOREIGN JUDGMENTS The clear aim of the Regulation is to make the recognition and enforcement of judgments easier as between the Member States. Article 36 of Regulation 1215/2012 provides that a judgment given in one Member State will be recognised in another Member States without any special procedure having to be followed.'),
                                                                                                                 ('Section 2: Chapter 2: Private International Law', 'Foundation Manual', 'According to Regulation 1215/2012, how is recognition of a foreign judgment handled?', 'qa', '{"answer":"Recognition is automatic without special procedures.","justification":"Article 36 of Regulation 1215/2012 provides that a judgment given in one Member State will be recognised in another Member States without any special procedure having to be followed."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Foundation'], 'BASIC PRINCIPLES This is the final major area of private international law: in what circumstances will a court in this jurisdiction recognise and enforce a judgment given by a court in another jurisdiction. Originally the subject of common law rules, this area was then governed by the Brussels Convention, rendering the situation somewhat clearer, at least as regards the Member States contracting to that convention. This has now been superseded by Regulation - see Regulation 1215/2012. REGULATION 1215/2012 RECOGNITION DISTINGUISHED FROM ENFORCEMENT It should be noted that recognition is different to enforcement in that a court could recognise a judgment given in another state without enforcing it. For instance, a judgment of a foreign court might become relevant in the course of proceedings in an Irish court. In this context, Articles 36-38 of Regulation 1215/2012 (previously Articles 33-37 of Regulation 44/2001) deal with the recognition of foreign judgments. On the other hand, a person who has received judgment against a defendant in a foreign court, and who wishes to enforce that judgment against assets of the defendant present in Ireland, would seek both recognition and enforcement. THE RECOGNITION OF FOREIGN JUDGMENTS The clear aim of the Regulation is to make the recognition and enforcement of judgments easier as between the Member States. Article 36 of Regulation 1215/2012 provides that a judgment given in one Member State will be recognised in another Member States without any special procedure having to be followed.'),
                                                                                                                 ('Section 2: Chapter 2: Private International Law', 'Foundation Manual', 'Can an Irish defendant use a foreign judgment as a bar against a new suit in Ireland?', 'qa', '{"answer":"Yes, even without formal recognition procedures.","justification":"if an Irish defendant is successful in a suit taken against him or her in another Member State, but is sued again in Ireland in relation to the same matter, he or she can plead the judgment of the foreign state as a bar against the action, even if no formal procedure has been followed for recognising the judgment."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Foundation'], 'Thus, if an Irish defendant is successful in a suit taken against him or her in another Member State, but is sued again in Ireland in relation to the same matter, he or she can plead the judgment of the foreign state as a bar against the action, even if no formal procedure has been followed for recognising the judgment. Article 45 of Regulation 1215/2012 sets out a number of limited exceptions to the recognition of judgments. It is worth noting these as they also apply to the enforcement of judgments (see below).'),
                                                                                                                 ('Section 2: Chapter 2: Private International Law', 'Foundation Manual', 'What regulation outlines exceptions to recognizing foreign judgments?', 'qa', '{"answer":"Regulation 1215/2012, specifically Article 45.","justification":"Article 45 of Regulation 1215/2012 sets out a number of limited exceptions to the recognition of judgments."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Foundation'], 'Thus, if an Irish defendant is successful in a suit taken against him or her in another Member State, but is sued again in Ireland in relation to the same matter, he or she can plead the judgment of the foreign state as a bar against the action, even if no formal procedure has been followed for recognising the judgment. Article 45 of Regulation 1215/2012 sets out a number of limited exceptions to the recognition of judgments. It is worth noting these as they also apply to the enforcement of judgments (see below).'),
                                                                                                                 ('Section 2: Chapter 2: Private International Law', 'Foundation Manual', 'Under what circumstances will recognition and enforcement of a foreign judgment not be granted?', 'qa', '{"answer":"If it conflicts with the provisions of sections 3,4,5 or 6 of Regulation 1215/2012 of Chapter of the Regulation, or if it is governed by a convention adopted with a third party state under Article 72.","justification":"Article 45 of Regulation 1215/2012 provides that recognition will not be granted and, by extension, enforcement not authorised if either conflicts with the provisions of sections 3,4,5 or 6 of Regulation 1215/2012 of Chapter of the Regulation. Similarly, Article 45 of 1215/2012 provides that recognition and enforcement will not follow in a case governed by a convention adopted with a third party state under Article 72."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Foundation'], 'In addition, Article 45 of Regulation 1215/2012 provides that recognition will not be granted and, by extension, enforcement not authorised if either conflicts with the provisions of sections 3,4,5 or 6 of Regulation 1215/2012 of Chapter of the Regulation. The sections deal with insurance contracts, consumer contracts with the addition of individual contracts of employment under 1215/2012, and the instances of exclusive jurisdiction listed in Article 22 already considered above. Similarly, Article 45 of 1215/2012 provides that recognition and enforcement will not follow in a case governed by a convention adopted with a third party state under Article 72. However, in examining these grounds of jurisdiction of the foreign court, the recognising court is bound by the findings of fact on which the court of the foreign state based its jurisdiction. ENFORCEMENT OF JUDGMENTS Regulation 1215/2012 provides that a judgment given in a Member State which is enforceable in that Member State shall be enforceable in the other Member States without any declaration of enforceability being required. Articles 39-51 of 1215/2012 deal with the enforcement of judgments. The party seeking enforcement shall provide the competent enforcement authority with: (a) a copy of the judgment which satisfies the conditions necessary to establish its authenticity; and the certificate issued pursuant to Article 53, certifying that the judgment is enforceable and containing an extract of the judgment as well as, where appropriate, relevant information on the recoverable costs of the proceedings and the calculation of interest.'),
                                                                                                                 ('Section 2: Chapter 2: Private International Law', 'Foundation Manual', 'What documents must be provided for the enforcement of a foreign judgment?', 'qa', '{"answer":"A copy of the judgment satisfying the conditions necessary to establish its authenticity and a certificate issued pursuant to Article 53, certifying that the judgment is enforceable and containing an extract of the judgment as well as, where appropriate, relevant information on the recoverable costs of the proceedings and the calculation of interest.","justification":"The party seeking enforcement shall provide the competent enforcement authority with: (a) a copy of the judgment which satisfies the conditions necessary to establish its authenticity; and the certificate issued pursuant to Article 53, certifying that the judgment is enforceable and containing an extract of the judgment as well as, where appropriate, relevant information on the recoverable costs of the proceedings and the calculation of interest."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Foundation'], 'In addition, Article 45 of Regulation 1215/2012 provides that recognition will not be granted and, by extension, enforcement not authorised if either conflicts with the provisions of sections 3,4,5 or 6 of Regulation 1215/2012 of Chapter of the Regulation. The sections deal with insurance contracts, consumer contracts with the addition of individual contracts of employment under 1215/2012, and the instances of exclusive jurisdiction listed in Article 22 already considered above. Similarly, Article 45 of 1215/2012 provides that recognition and enforcement will not follow in a case governed by a convention adopted with a third party state under Article 72. However, in examining these grounds of jurisdiction of the foreign court, the recognising court is bound by the findings of fact on which the court of the foreign state based its jurisdiction. ENFORCEMENT OF JUDGMENTS Regulation 1215/2012 provides that a judgment given in a Member State which is enforceable in that Member State shall be enforceable in the other Member States without any declaration of enforceability being required. Articles 39-51 of 1215/2012 deal with the enforcement of judgments. The party seeking enforcement shall provide the competent enforcement authority with: (a) a copy of the judgment which satisfies the conditions necessary to establish its authenticity; and the certificate issued pursuant to Article 53, certifying that the judgment is enforceable and containing an extract of the judgment as well as, where appropriate, relevant information on the recoverable costs of the proceedings and the calculation of interest.'),
                                                                                                                 ('Section 2: Chapter 2: Private International Law', 'Foundation Manual', 'What is one requirement for enforcing a foreign judgment under traditional rules?', 'qa', '{"answer":"The foreign court must have had jurisdiction under Irish conflicts rules.","justification":"First, the foreign court has to have had jurisdiction under Irish conflicts rules."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Foundation'], 'The Rules of Court require that the party seeking enforcement produce an affidavit of service of the certificate issued by the court of origin pursuant to Article 53 of Regulation 1215/2012 in the manner provided by Article 43 of Regulation No. 1215/2012. (High Court -see Order 42A (as amended); Circuit Court see Order 61A as amended; District Court see Order (as amended)). See the text of the Regulation and the Rules of the appropriate court for further information. THE TRADITIONAL RULES Outside the geographical and subject-matter context of the Regulations and Conventions, the traditional rules still apply. Briefly, the following are the requirements for the enforcement of a foreign judgment. First, the foreign court has to have had jurisdiction under Irish conflicts rules. The rules on this are complex. Secondly, the foreign judgment has to have been final and conclusive.'),
                                                                                                                 ('Section 2: Chapter 2: Private International Law', 'Foundation Manual', 'What is another requirement for enforcing a foreign judgment under traditional rules?', 'qa', '{"answer":"The foreign judgment must have been final and conclusive.","justification":"Secondly, the foreign judgment has to have been final and conclusive."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Foundation'], 'The Rules of Court require that the party seeking enforcement produce an affidavit of service of the certificate issued by the court of origin pursuant to Article 53 of Regulation 1215/2012 in the manner provided by Article 43 of Regulation No. 1215/2012. (High Court -see Order 42A (as amended); Circuit Court see Order 61A as amended; District Court see Order (as amended)). See the text of the Regulation and the Rules of the appropriate court for further information. THE TRADITIONAL RULES Outside the geographical and subject-matter context of the Regulations and Conventions, the traditional rules still apply. Briefly, the following are the requirements for the enforcement of a foreign judgment. First, the foreign court has to have had jurisdiction under Irish conflicts rules. The rules on this are complex. Secondly, the foreign judgment has to have been final and conclusive.'),
                                                                                                                 ('Section 2: Chapter 2: Private International Law', 'Foundation Manual', 'What does the term ''torpedo actions'' refer to in the context of Regulation 1215/2012?', 'qa', '{"answer":"Proceedings wrongly commenced in one Member State court to delay any proceedings in the chosen court.","justification":"This ruling encouraged ''torpedo'' actions whereby proceedings are (wrongly) commenced in one Member State court to delay any proceedings in the chosen court."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Foundation'], 'While Regulation 1215/2012 (Brussels 1 recast) contains largely the same provisions as the Regulation it replaced (i.e. Regulation 44/2001) - set out below are some of the main changes that were introduced. EXCLUSIVE JURISDICTION CLAUSES AND ''TORPEDO'' ACTIONS One of the most controversial aspects of the Brussels Regulation had been the strict interpretation of its lis pendens rules as adopted by the CJEU in Erich Gasser GmbH -vMISAT Srl. Case The case established that where proceedings are brought first in one Member State, all other Member State courts must stay any proceedings involving the same parties and same cause of action pending the first seized court''s decision on jurisdiction. This is so even when those proceedings have been brought in breach of an exclusive jurisdiction clause in favour of another Member State court and irrespective of the amount of time that the jurisdictional issues will take to resolve (in this respect, some courts take much longer than others). This ruling encouraged ''torpedo'' actions whereby proceedings are (wrongly) commenced in one Member State court to delay any proceedings in the chosen court. An example of the tactical use of a torpedo action occurred in the Morgan Europe Ltd Primacom [2005] EWHC 508. Cooke observed that: ...'),
                                                                                                                 ('Section 2: Chapter 2: Private International Law', 'Foundation Manual', 'What does the recast Brussels Regulation (Regulation address?', 'qa', '{"answer":"It addresses the issue where courts other than the first seised must stay their proceedings pending a decision by the court first seised.","justification":"The recast Brussels Regulation (Regulation addresses this problem. There is an exception to the previously absolute rule that any court other than the first seised must stay its proceedings pending a decision by the court first seised."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Foundation'], 'it is clear that both these proceedings [in Mainz and Frankfurt] were commenced in breach of the exclusive jurisdiction clause and the evidence suggests that this was done with the primary intention of frustrating any possible attempt by [the banks] to seek appropriate relief in the English Courts in accordance with the jurisdiction clause. The Mainz proceedings were, after some considerable delay, served on all the [banks] but the Frankfurt proceedings have not yet been served on a number of the [banks]. It is clear that delay is advantageous to Primacom and this appears to be one of its objectives. The judge went on to state that it was ..difficult to see how the German Courts could find that they are entitled to exercise jurisdiction in the face of the exclusive jurisdiction clause" in the facility agreement (para [34]), but concluded that he was still obliged to stay proceedings in England pending a decision by the German courts because the German courts had been seised of the dispute first. The German courts eventually agreed with the English judge''s analysis that they had no jurisdiction to hear the dispute, but only after much expense and delay. The recast Brussels Regulation (Regulation addresses this problem. There is an exception to the previously absolute rule that any court other than the first seised must stay its proceedings pending a decision by the court first seised.'),
                                                                                                                 ('Section 2: Chapter 2: Private International Law', 'Foundation Manual', 'Why did the judge conclude that proceedings in England should be stayed pending a decision by the German courts?', 'qa', '{"answer":"Because the German courts had been seised of the dispute first.","justification":"but concluded that he was still obliged to stay proceedings in England pending a decision by the German courts because the German courts had been seised of the dispute first."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Foundation'], 'it is clear that both these proceedings [in Mainz and Frankfurt] were commenced in breach of the exclusive jurisdiction clause and the evidence suggests that this was done with the primary intention of frustrating any possible attempt by [the banks] to seek appropriate relief in the English Courts in accordance with the jurisdiction clause. The Mainz proceedings were, after some considerable delay, served on all the [banks] but the Frankfurt proceedings have not yet been served on a number of the [banks]. It is clear that delay is advantageous to Primacom and this appears to be one of its objectives. The judge went on to state that it was ..difficult to see how the German Courts could find that they are entitled to exercise jurisdiction in the face of the exclusive jurisdiction clause" in the facility agreement (para [34]), but concluded that he was still obliged to stay proceedings in England pending a decision by the German courts because the German courts had been seised of the dispute first. The German courts eventually agreed with the English judge''s analysis that they had no jurisdiction to hear the dispute, but only after much expense and delay. The recast Brussels Regulation (Regulation addresses this problem. There is an exception to the previously absolute rule that any court other than the first seised must stay its proceedings pending a decision by the court first seised.'),
                                                                                                                 ('Section 2: Chapter 2: Private International Law', 'Foundation Manual', 'What happens when parties confer exclusive jurisdiction on a particular court under Article 31(2)?', 'qa', '{"answer":"That court may proceed to hear the case even if it was not first seised.","justification":"Under Article 31(2) of the recast Regulation, if the parties have conferred exclusive jurisdiction on a particular court, that court may proceed to hear the case even if it was not first seised."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Foundation'], 'Under Article 31(2) of the recast Regulation, if the parties have conferred exclusive jurisdiction on a particular court, that court may proceed to hear the case even if it was not first seised. All other courts must halt their proceedings once the designated court has established that it has jurisdiction (article 31(3)) or possibly as soon as the chosen court is seised (recital (22)). ABOLITION OF THE EXEQUATUR Exequatur is the procedure for the declaration of enforceability of a judgement given in another member state. In general this has been implemented in Regulation 1215/2012 and the requirement for a declaration of enforceability has been removed. Regulation 1215/2012 provides that a judgment given in another member state which is enforceable in that member state shall be enforceable in the other member states without a declaration of enforceability being required, upon production of a copy of the judgment which satisfies the conditions necessary to establish its authenticity and a certificate to be issued by the court of origin. The regulation does provide for certain grounds where a court may refuse to recognise and/or enforce a judgment. (Article 45 and 46). Other changes include: * Extension of the jurisdiction rules in the Brussels Regulation to disputes involving defendants who are not domiciled in an Member State * Improvement of the interface between the Brussels Regulation and arbitration * Better coordination of parallel proceedings * Clarification on the circulation of provisional and protective measures in the'),
                                                                                                                 ('Section 2: Chapter 2: Private International Law', 'Foundation Manual', 'What is the effect of abolishing exequatur under Regulation 1215/2012?', 'qa', '{"answer":"A judgment given in another member state which is enforceable in that member state shall be enforceable in the other member states without a declaration of enforceability being required.","justification":"Regulation 1215/2012 provides that a judgment given in another member state which is enforceable in that member state shall be enforceable in the other member states without a declaration of enforceability being required, upon production of a copy of the judgment which satisfies the conditions necessary to establish its authenticity and a certificate to be issued by the court of origin."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Foundation'], 'Under Article 31(2) of the recast Regulation, if the parties have conferred exclusive jurisdiction on a particular court, that court may proceed to hear the case even if it was not first seised. All other courts must halt their proceedings once the designated court has established that it has jurisdiction (article 31(3)) or possibly as soon as the chosen court is seised (recital (22)). ABOLITION OF THE EXEQUATUR Exequatur is the procedure for the declaration of enforceability of a judgement given in another member state. In general this has been implemented in Regulation 1215/2012 and the requirement for a declaration of enforceability has been removed. Regulation 1215/2012 provides that a judgment given in another member state which is enforceable in that member state shall be enforceable in the other member states without a declaration of enforceability being required, upon production of a copy of the judgment which satisfies the conditions necessary to establish its authenticity and a certificate to be issued by the court of origin. The regulation does provide for certain grounds where a court may refuse to recognise and/or enforce a judgment. (Article 45 and 46). Other changes include: * Extension of the jurisdiction rules in the Brussels Regulation to disputes involving defendants who are not domiciled in an Member State * Improvement of the interface between the Brussels Regulation and arbitration * Better coordination of parallel proceedings * Clarification on the circulation of provisional and protective measures in the'),
                                                                                                                 ('Section 2: Chapter 2: Private International Law', 'Foundation Manual', 'What is the date the Convention on Choice of Court Agreements was signed into Irish law?', 'qa', '{"answer":"November 2015","justification":"The Convention on Choice of Court Agreements (concluded at the Hague June 2005) was signed into Irish law on the November 2015 by way of the Choice of Court (Hague Convention) Act 2015."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Foundation'], 'The Convention on Choice of Court Agreements (concluded at the Hague June 2005) was signed into Irish law on the November 2015 by way of the Choice of Court (Hague Convention) Act 2015. The Convention deals with international cases involving "exclusive choice of court agreements concluded in civil and commercial matters". At present, the Convention is only binding on member states (Denmark with certain exceptions), Mexico, Singapore and Montenegro. While other countries are signatories to the Convention, they have yet to ratify it. While the Convention applies to choice of court agreements concluded in civil and commercial matters, Article 2 sets out a number of exclusions, for example, employment contracts, family matters, consumer contracts, the status and legal capacity of natural persons, wills and succession, insolvency, personal injuries. However, Article 2 also states that such proceedings are not excluded from the scope of this Convention where such a matter arises merely as a preliminary question and not as an object of the proceedings. In particular, the mere fact that a matter excluded arises by way of defence does not exclude proceedings from the Convention, if that matter is not an object of the proceedings. The 2015 Act provides that an application to enforce a judgment in Ireland should be made to the Master of the High Court, ex-parte. Order of the Rules of the Superior Courts sets out in detail the matters that should be contained in an affidavit to ground any such application.'),
                                                                                                                 ('Section 2: Chapter 2: Private International Law', 'Foundation Manual', 'To whom is the Convention on Choice of Court Agreements currently binding?', 'qa', '{"answer":"member states (with certain exceptions for Denmark), Mexico, Singapore, and Montenegro","justification":"At present, the Convention is only binding on member states (Denmark with certain exceptions), Mexico, Singapore and Montenegro."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Foundation'], 'The Convention on Choice of Court Agreements (concluded at the Hague June 2005) was signed into Irish law on the November 2015 by way of the Choice of Court (Hague Convention) Act 2015. The Convention deals with international cases involving "exclusive choice of court agreements concluded in civil and commercial matters". At present, the Convention is only binding on member states (Denmark with certain exceptions), Mexico, Singapore and Montenegro. While other countries are signatories to the Convention, they have yet to ratify it. While the Convention applies to choice of court agreements concluded in civil and commercial matters, Article 2 sets out a number of exclusions, for example, employment contracts, family matters, consumer contracts, the status and legal capacity of natural persons, wills and succession, insolvency, personal injuries. However, Article 2 also states that such proceedings are not excluded from the scope of this Convention where such a matter arises merely as a preliminary question and not as an object of the proceedings. In particular, the mere fact that a matter excluded arises by way of defence does not exclude proceedings from the Convention, if that matter is not an object of the proceedings. The 2015 Act provides that an application to enforce a judgment in Ireland should be made to the Master of the High Court, ex-parte. Order of the Rules of the Superior Courts sets out in detail the matters that should be contained in an affidavit to ground any such application.'),
                                                                                                                 ('Section 2: Chapter 2: Private International Law', 'Foundation Manual', 'What regulation provides a mechanism for enforcing judgments in civil and commercial matters when all contracting parties are within the', 'qa', '{"answer":"Regulation 1215/2012","justification":"Regulation 1215/2012 already provides a mechanism for the enforcement of judgments in exclusive and non-exclusive choice of court agreements in civil and commercial matters (see above)."}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Foundation'], 'Note that where all the contracting parties are resident within the Regulation 1215/2012 already provides a mechanism for the enforcement of judgments in exclusive and non-exclusive choice of court agreements in civil and commercial matters (see above).'),
                                                                                                                 ('Section 2: Chapter 2: Private International Law', 'Foundation Manual', 'In what context does Regulation 1215/2012 apply for enforcing judgments?', 'qa', '{"answer":"When all contracting parties are resident within the","justification":"where all the contracting parties are resident within the"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Foundation'], 'Note that where all the contracting parties are resident within the Regulation 1215/2012 already provides a mechanism for the enforcement of judgments in exclusive and non-exclusive choice of court agreements in civil and commercial matters (see above).'),
                                                                                                                 ('Section 2: Chapter 2: Private International Law', 'Foundation Manual', 'What regulation is referenced in Appendix A?', 'qa', '{"answer":"REGULATION 1215/2012 JURISDICTION AND RECOGNITION AND ENFORCEMENT OF JUDGMENTS IN CIVIL AND COMMERCIAL MATTERS (RECAST)","justification":"REGULATION 1215/2012 JURISDICTION AND RECOGNITION AND ENFORCEMENT OF JUDGMENTS IN CIVIL AND COMMERCIAL MATTERS (RECAST)"}'::jsonb, ARRAY['AI', 'Foundation'], 'APPENDICES (LIST) SEE MOODLE FOR LINKS TO THE FOLLOWING APPENDIX A REGULATION 1215/2012 JURISDICTION AND RECOGNITION AND ENFORCEMENT OF JUDGMENTS IN CIVIL AND COMMERCIAL MATTERS (RECAST) Link to Regulation 1215 of 2012 APPENDIX JURISDICTION OF COURTS & ENFORCEMENT OF'),
